{"title":"Satellite","characters":[["ANDERSON","Bella"],["ANNOUNCER","English Male 2"],["BARBARA","Barbara"],["BATES","Adam"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","Antoni"],["BRODY","Dan Brody"],["CAVELL","English Male 3"],["CHERI","Hannah - Raspy British Female Voice 1"],["FISCHER","Fischer"],["FREDDY","English Male 4"],["GROUND CONTROL","chizzo"],["ISABELLE","Elli"],["JACKSON","Josh"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","Rachel"],["KYLE","English Male 2"],["MCGREW","English Male 3"],["MILLER","English Male 4"],["MR. KEPLER","chizzo"],["NARRATOR","Story Teller"],["PENROSE","Penrose (American)"],["PHOEBE","Bella"],["SERGEANT","English Male 2"],["SOLDIER","English Male 3"],["TATE","English Male 4"],["TOM","Tom"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Elli"],["VOLKOV","English Male 4"],["WARBURG","English Male 2"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","English Male 3"]],"voice_data":[["-","-","-"],["Rachel",null,"21m00Tcm4TlvDq8ikWAM"],["Domi",null,"AZnzlk1XvdvUeBnXmlld"],["Bella",null,"EXAVITQu4vr4xnSDxMaL"],["Antoni",null,"ErXwobaYiN019PkySvjV"],["Elli",null,"MF3mGyEYCl7XYWbV9V6O"],["Josh",null,"TxGEqnHWrfWFTfGW9XjX"],["Arnold",null,"VR6AewLTigWG4xSOukaG"],["Adam",null,"pNInz6obpgDQGcFmaJgB"],["Sam",null,"yoZ06aMxZJJ28mfd3POQ"],["Dan Brody","","7XCWpj6v0QsecU8Oi0D7"],["Faulkner","","7oXlp8BhpDQmpz2w3oEc"],["Penrose (American)","","8iOakx12I2plFgbcdFAC"],["chizzo","anglo-italian male","Bsja4MX4wSWt1eQiOn5n"],["Story Teller",null,"C894Rlpp6ZQr793LKu0r"],["[DramaBooks] Peter",null,"EHhKJrdzNORbaf4h8hK1"],["Billy:  Earnest Character!",null,"HQpGCMz1x58FIOUK5nAh"],["Hannah - Raspy British Female Voice 1","","HWZv11bgPX2kFQXexvy4"],["Fischer","","IQWy3nYrudW8XpkxiTvI"],["Tom",null,"KYahJqjUETABsjV3bQWs"],["Morson","Mid-atlantic male","MTWNMFT6MxuyS5LvJevh"],["English Male 2","Englishman 2","OE3oV6GvwZZxmbleiW6e"],["[ElevenVoices] African Male Raspy","","QK9pRG9Kr3p95jN6FaFQ"],["Barbara","","pVMxH1FoLtJHnNqJkbBX"],["English Male 3","Englishman3","pXL2iPuFUPZFZTNLRZoC"],["English Male 4","Englishman4","vJgomBtyGJZXMjVXYdtN"]],"script":[["NARRATOR","FADE IN:",1,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. LIVING ROOM - NIGHT",1,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The living room of an ordinary house in an ordinary road.\n    ",2,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Despite the room being empty, the television has been left on. It is tuned to the Great British Shopping Experience, a shopping channel. \n    ",2,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the television: Dan BRODY (slick, handsome, camp) is going through his sales patter.\n    ",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Body bags!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Body bags!!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Body bags!!!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Body bags!!!!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Papa’s got a brand new body bag!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Don’t ask me how, but we’ve managed to get hold of a brand new batch of body bags!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Now you may remember the last time we had these on sale we sold out all five thousand within an hour and had to disappoint a lot of people. Were you one of those sad unfortunates? If so, what are you waiting for? Get on that phone right now and grab yourself a bargain!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","You’ve seen similar body bags selling for ridiculous amounts of money and maybe been tempted to buy a few. Well - don’t!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Save your money and get the real deal for a whole lot less right here, right now on the Great British Shopping Experience, the only shopping channel that doesn’t rip you off!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","These are the best body bags money can buy and they come with a lifetime guarantee.",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Just don’t ask how we got hold of them or why we’re banging them out for the stupidly cheap price of forty-nine ninety-nine each! That, ladies and gentlemen, is our little secret.",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","These body bags are totally waterproof, so no embarrassing leakages. They’re coated in insect-repellent, which will keep those nasty house flies at bay. I mean, who wants to see their loved ones turned into maggot meat? \n      Yeuk\n      !",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","And look how tough this material is. Any stray dog thinking they’re going to make a meal of your \n      nana\n       is in for a major disappointment.",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","Can body bags fly? You bet they can! Straight out that door and onto your doorstep in next to no time!",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","But seemingly not just yet. A voice in my ear - a.k.a. Madame La Producer, a.k.a. She Who Must Be Obeyed - is telling me it's time for beddy-byes.",2,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","CAMERA tracks to the doorway and out into --\n    ",2,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. HALLWAY - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS",2,"-","No"],["BRODY","The Black Knight cometh, its wicked ways to perform, and so we have to leave it there for now. Please don't bother phoning. All the lines are now closed until the Black Knight has passed by once more. But worry ye not. We’ll be opening them again the moment it's safe to do so.",3,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","CAMERA tracks up the stairs into -\n    ",3,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. bedrOOM - NIGHT",3,"-","No"],["BRODY","So this is me, Dan Brody, saying toodle-pip and may I on behalf of everyone here at the Great British Shopping Experience wish you and your loved ones a safe transition?",4,"-","No"],["BRODY","Bye, folks. See you tomorrow.",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","TOM Caxton (in a red track suit) is tying up his wife, BARBARA (in a blue track suit).\n    ",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Kneeling on the bed, Barbara is completely compliant as Tom skillfully binds her. Next to her on the bed is a book on Shibari, the Japanese art of knot tying.\n    ",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When he is done tying up Barbara, Tom checks the ropes and knots. Then he helps Barbara get comfortable and pulls the bedclothes over her before kissing her tenderly on the forehead.\n    ",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","They exchange anxious looks, offer each other re-assuring smiles. Neither is keen for Tom to go but he has to.\n    ",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","We follow a reluctant Tom out on to -\n    ",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. LANDING - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS",4,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom locks the bedroom door.\n    ",5,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He goes downstairs to -\n    ",5,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. HALLWAY - NIGHT - CONTINUOUS",5,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A table has been placed against the front door. Tom takes a moment to check it.\n    ",6,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then heads into -\n    ",6,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - night - coNTINUOUS",6,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom picks up a transistor radio from the table and turns it on. It makes no noise.\n    ",7,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From a bottle of whisky, he takes two nerve-steadying gulps.\n    ",7,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then he goes outside into -\n    ",7,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. Back garden - night - contiNUOUS",7,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom locks the kitchen door behind himself.\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He inspects an ants nest in the corner of his patio. Watches dispassionately as the ants go about their business.\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His transistor radio starts pumping out a series of bleeps, each about one second apart.\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...... BLEEP...... BLEEP......\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The sound is somewhat reminiscent of a hospital heart monitor.\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The interval between bleeps gradually narrows as the bleeps grow louder and more urgent.\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...! BLEEP...! BLEEP...!\n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom hurries into - \n    ",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Shed - night - contiNUOUS",8,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","An old mattress and a couple of pillows have been placed on the floor.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...! BLEEP...! BLEEP...!\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The bleeps are about a tenth of a second apart now.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Anxiety is writ large on Tom’s face.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He throws himself onto the mattress and places the transistor radio close to his ear.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...! BLEEP...! BLEEP...!\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The bleeps rise to a crescendo. Tom fights to control his terror. He claws at the mattress. Buries his face in a pillow.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The bleeps blend one into the other as the shed suddenly fills with sickly green light.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom thrashes. Spasms.\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From the radio comes a single, unending tone:\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEP!\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom opens his mouth to scream. But before he can make a sound -\n    ",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLACKOUT:",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. Back garden - morning",9,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FADE IN:",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","To the sound of BIRD SONG and a CLOSE-UP of the ants nest.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Camera PANS OUT. Takes in the rest of the garden. Seems like just another ordinary day in suburbia until -\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The peace is disturbed by the shed door being abruptly pushed open.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, looking like he’s barely slept, staggers out of the shed. Trips. Lands on his knees.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","At first, he doesn’t bother getting up. He takes long, deep breaths of morning air.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In the distance -\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","GUN SHOTS. POLICE SIRENS. More GUN SHOTS.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","SILENCE.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom barely reacts to these intimations of violence. Not so the sound of GROANING which draws his attention to a badly mutilated INTRUDER sitting against the garden fence with his guts spilled on his lap.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom betrays no emotion as he briefly disappears behind the shed and returns with a garden spade.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Standing over the Intruder, he raises the spade. Brings it swiftly down, catching the Intruder on the side of his neck.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He strikes again and again. Hacking at the Intruder’s neck until his head flies off.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Casting aside the spade, Tom drags the Intruder’s body into the rhubarb patch. As he does so, we see the legs of another DEAD MAN sticking out from the rhubarb.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom takes the Intruder’s head and tosses it into the rhubarb patch.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His brutal act of killing has invigorated Tom. Panting, smiling grimly, he leans against the shed and masturbates vigorously. The resulting orgasm arrives quickly and is intense.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","After adjusting his dress, Tom makes his way to the garden tap. Turns on the tap. Washes his face. Drinks.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom dries his hands and face with his tracksuit top.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A distant SCREAM OF HORROR is followed by the SOUND OF BREAKING GLASS, both of which Tom ignores.\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He unlocks the kitchen door and goes into -\n    ",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. KiTCHEN - moRNING - continuous",10,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Through the kitchen into -\n    ",11,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. HALLWAY - morning - continuous",11,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom quickly checks that the front door is still intact and the table is undisturbed. Then he goes upstairs to -\n    ",12,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. LANDING - morning - conTINUOUS",12,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom unlocks the bedroom door.\n    ",13,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Hesitates.\n    ",13,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Full of trepidation, he opens the door.\n    ",13,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes into the -\n    ",13,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. BedROOM - moRNING - conTINUOUS",13,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As Tom enters Barbara - much to his relief - is still trussed up on the bed.\n    ",14,"-","No"],["BARBARA","About bloody time. I need a \n      piss\n      .",14,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",14,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara, dressed in a red tracksuit, is on the settee, watching Dan Brody on the Great British Shopping Experience channel.\n    ",15,"-","No"],["BRODY","Hey, hey, hey! Dan Brody here, folks - back to lavish upon you a veritable cornucopia of consumer goodies! Before we get started though, I have to pass on the sad news that my Great British Shopping Experience co-star and dear, dear friend, Hannah Newton, did not survive the last transit, so she won't be joining us today - or indeed ever again.",15,"-","No"],["BRODY","Hannah, my love, I'm sure you can hear me from up there in that Great Shopping Mall in the Sky and I want you to know that everyone here at the Great British Shopping Experience and your thousands upon thousands of fans are missing you already. Also, Martin is sincerely sorry that he gouged out your eyes and ate your liver. He knows that was very naughty of him and he says he hopes you didn’t suffer too much.",15,"-","No"],["BRODY","But even with Hannah gone, life goes on and so do the bargains on the Great British Shopping Experience - case in point being this authentic reproduction \n      Fabergé\n       egg which is an exact copy of one in the Paris Louvre that used to belong to none other than the Empress Josephine herself.",15,"-","No"],["BRODY","Oh yes, I can hear your \n      ooh\n      s\n       and \n      aah\n      s\n       from here. Just imagine how green with envy your friends will be when they see this magnificent work of art sitting on your mantelpiece.",15,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Bored and having no interest in acquiring an ornamental egg, Barbara sighs and takes herself out to - \n    ",15,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - day",15,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara gets out the ingredients of a decent fried breakfast - eggs, bacon, sausages, tomatoes, black pudding, mushrooms.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","She throws them in a frying pan on the gas stove and watches them sizzle.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Now and then she flips over a food item with a spatula.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara is truly content.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","But then - \n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The stove goes out.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Alarmed, Barbara turns the gas off and back on. She tries lighting it.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Nothing.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","There is no gas.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Dazed, defeated, she sits at the kitchen table and sobs.  A great reservoir of suppressed fear and frustration is released in a tsunami of emotion.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom enters. He is wearing a blue track suit and drying his hair.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Immediately taking stock of the situation, throws the towel over the back of a chair. Plays with the gas stove trying to get it to light. Gives up on the stupid thing.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He grabs a bowl from the cupboard. Pours the contents of the frying pan into the bowl. Puts the bowl in the microwave and turns on the microwave.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then he sits opposite Barbara and takes her hands in his.\n    ",16,"-","No"],["BARBARA","It’s not my fault.",16,"-","No"],["TOM","Why don’t you go watch the telly, Barbara? I’ll bring you a nice cup of tea and some toast.",16,"-","No"],["BARBARA","No bread.",16,"-","No"],["TOM","I think we have Ryvita.",16,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I’d prefer cereal.",16,"-","No"],["TOM","Cereal it is.",16,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Cornflakes.",16,"-","No"],["TOM","Sure.",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",16,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara are seated at the table. \n    ",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara, whose mood has improved since the kitchen incident, has a bowl of cornflakes and a cup of tea in front of her. \n    ",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is faced with a soggy mass of half-fried breakfast items that have been microwaved.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Go on then. Eat up.",17,"-","No"],["TOM","You first, my sweet.",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","OK.",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara scoops up a spoonful of cornflakes, chews and swallows.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Now you, Tom.",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","With a forced grin, Tom uses his fork to pick up some of his breakfast. He pops it in his mouth.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Obviously not enjoying it, he chews and swallows.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["TOM","Hmm. Delicious.",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Have some more.",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom pats his stomach.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["TOM","I’m full, Barbara. Couldn't eat another thing.",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Well, no point wasting good food. Stick it in the fridge. You can have it for your supper.",17,"-","No"],["TOM","You, my dear, are a bloody sadist.",17,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Says the man who ties his wife up every night.",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom points to something in his bowl.\n    ",17,"-","No"],["TOM","I think that used to be a mushroom.",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Tom’s office - day",17,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The spare bedroom. Tom has a PC set up on a desk. Also in the room are an armchair and a television.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom signs into an online work meeting. \n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His PC screen is divided into four quarters. In one, he can see himself sat at his PC. The other three are each occupied by one of his work colleagues. These are KYLE Lynton, CHERI \n      Mahler\n       and FREDDY Benedict.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As Tom joins, Freddy and Kyle are in the middle of a conversation.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","It makes sense though, doesn't it? Despite what they tell you, Soviet weaponry was lightyears ahead of anything NATO could drum up.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Bullshit. Total and utter bullshit! The one and only time the Ruskies sent a craft to the moon, it crash landed. And you’re telling me they managed to get a whole army up there in one piece? Don’t be a twat.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Open your eyes, Kyle, use your brain and do a bit of research. Look on the Internet and you’ll find a ton of evidence.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Such as, Freddy?",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Photographs for a start.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Hello? You ever hear of a thing called Photoshop?",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","And there's this guy - Michael Rogers - used to work for the CIA. His job was to monitor first the Nazi moon base and then the Soviet one. I'll send you a link to his website.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Kyle snorts his contempt.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","If you kids have quite finished talking total bollocks, perhaps we can get on with the meeting?",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Please let’s do. Freddy’s weird bullshit is doing my head in.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Weird it might be. Bullshit it ain’t.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Morning, Tom! Pity you didn’t dial in earlier. You’d have heard Freddy’s latest gem - something about the Black Knight being an old Soviet doomsday weapon that got forgotten about when Yeltsin dismantled the USSR.",18,"-","No"],["TOM","To be honest, Kyle, I don’t give a flying \n      fuck\n       about the Black Knight right now. I just want to get this meeting out of the way so I can get on with my work.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","What’s the bloody point? In case you hadn't noticed, the world's about to end.",18,"-","No"],["TOM","So why are you here, Kyle? Why are you even bothering to show your ugly mug?",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Filthy lucre, dear boy. Some of us have mortgages, you know.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Before we get started, I have some sad news to impart.  You've probably noticed John Wickerby isn't with us today. I’m afraid he won't be with us tomorrow either - or in fact ever again. In the early hours of this morning, he shot himself in the head with a nail gun.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Dead?",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Very.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Are you sure you have that right, Cheri? I’ve never heard of the Black Knight making people shoot themselves.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","What happened is this: During the last transit, John attacked both his children, leaving one of them dead and the other missing half her face. When he came out of his fugue and saw what he'd done, he smothered the surviving child with a pillow. He then killed his wife by slitting her throat with a Stanley knife before doing the same to his dog.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Not Buddy? I really liked Buddy.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","John left me a video message - which for the sake of decency I won't play for you - describing what he had done. At the end, he put a nail gun to his head, shouted, “\n      E.T\n      ., fuck off!” \n      and\n       shot himself.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Silence follows as the conference attendees take in the news.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then -\n    ",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","I call dibs on his parking space.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","You callous, unfeeling shit.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Frankly, Kyle, I hope when we meet tomorrow Cheri will be telling us how you were found with your throat ripped out and a rat feasting on your genitalia.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Not me, baby. If one person is going to survive this shit show, it's Kyle Alexander Lynton esquire.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Look at you! A man you've worked with for over a decade has killed himself. His wife is dead. His children are dead. And you're calling dibs on his parking space!",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Yeah, well, you know who else has died in the past twenty four hours, Freddy? Millions of people!",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","I saw on the news this morning that since the Black Knight started shitting all over mankind, half a billion people have pegged it!",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Half a fucking billion! That’s a sixteenth of the entire human race. Gone!",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Against that, one neurotic accounts manager, his - let's face it - barely shaggable wife and a couple of brats don't matter a whole hill of proverbials.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Closing her eyes and placing her hands over her ears, Cheri screams.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Stop it, stop it, stop it!",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","Jeez, Cheri. Chill out will you? We were only joshing.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","No we weren’t.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","You’re fired, Kyle.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","You what?",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","You are no longer an employee of Lovecraft Wonder Toys. Pack up your shit and go.",18,"-","No"],["KYLE","You can’t do that, Cheri. Who the fuck do you -",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","With a click of a mouse, Cheri unceremoniously ejects Kyle from the meeting.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Anyone else want to tell me what I can and can’t do?",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Well done, Cheri. The little shit had that coming.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Perhaps now we can get on with the meeting.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","First up on the agenda is a meeting I had last night with the marketing department. It’s been decided to permanently mothball Sister Gabriella and Father Dominique.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","What? You’ve got to be shitting us. Gabby and Dom are the most popular dolls in retail history.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Were\n      , Freddy. Were. Our three biggest buyers have cancelled all future orders for both dolls and we’re expecting others to follow suit.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","But why in God’s name? Why?",18,"-","No"],["TOM","Because we’re fucked, Freddy. Well and truly fucked. The world is going down the crapper and the last thing your average kiddy wants to play with in the middle of a cannibal apocalypse is a vigilante nun.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Spot on, Tom. There’s been a seismic change in the toy market and if we don’t adapt, we die and so, after some hasty market research, our braniacs in development have come up with this.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Cheri clicks her mouse. Up pops a picture of a chainsaw-wielding, leather-jacketed doll.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Gentlemen, may I introduce the latest addition to the Lovecraft Wonder Toys family of dolls - the one and only Butcher Baby!",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A moment’s silence as Tom and Freddy take in what they’re seeing and hearing.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then -\n    ",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Fucking hell! That’s beautiful.",18,"-","No"],["TOM","It’s monstrous.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","It’s beautiful \n      and\n       monstrous and it’s going to outsell every other doll in history.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","I can’t see it. I mean, no sane parent is going to buy something like that for their kids.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Show me a sane parent and I’ll show you someone who hasn’t been paying attention. With all the shit that’s been going on, anyone not at least slightly bonkers has something seriously wrong with them.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Besides which, when did parents have any say in what they buy their kids? They might not like Butcher Baby but when that little brat of theirs starts screaming, “I want a Butcher Baby! I want a Butcher Baby!” out comes that bank card and - \n      kerching!\n       - there goes another Butcher Baby.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","It’s called pester power, Freddy.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Pester power!",18,"-","No"],["TOM","I have to be honest. I can’t bloody wait to get my hands on one of those things.",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Bit old to be playing with dolls, aren’t you?",18,"-","No"],["TOM","I'm going to buy me a dozen. No - two dozen. And I’m going to steal my neighbour’s gnomes and replace them with Butcher Babies.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","As usual, we’ll be creating a comic strip to promote the new brand. Tom, as you’re the only comic strip wallah on the team who hasn’t died in a disgusting manner, I’m leaving that in your capable hands. How soon can you knock up some panels?",18,"-","No"],["TOM","I’ll have something for you by close of play today. Do we have any scripts yet?",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Marketing have come up with one but they want to run it through the usual focus groups before letting us loose on it. In the meantime, I suggest you use an old Sister Gabriella script.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Freddy, now that Kyle is on the scrap heap where he belongs, I’m putting you in charge of the sales drive. Think you can handle it?",18,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Abso-bloody-lutely\n      . I’ve been waiting a long time for this.",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Put out the word to the sales force that it's double commission. You might also mention that anyone not hitting their targets is out on their \n      arse\n      .",18,"-","No"],["CHERI","Now, if you’ll excuse me, gentlemen, I have another meeting to endure.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Cheri and Freddy both leave the meeting.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits staring at his screen. Something is bothering him.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Something doesn’t seem quite right.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He summons up the recording of the meeting. Rewinds it a bit. Pauses. Focuses in on Cheri. Zooms in over her shoulder - onto the cuckoo clock on the wall behind her.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Smiles.\n    ",18,"-","No"],["TOM","Well, well, well. You old sly boots.",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",18,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Cheri is on the settee watching Dan Brody extolling the dubious qualities of some worthless piece of tat.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom bursts in. Excited. Gleeful.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["TOM","You’ll never guess what?",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara mutes the sound on the television.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","You’re off for a dirty weekend with Taylor Swift?",19,"-","No"],["TOM","Better than that!",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Do tell.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","I was in a meeting just now and something I saw on the screen was bothering me but I couldn’t work out just what. So I replayed the meeting, froze the picture and zoomed in behind Cheri. And do you know what was on the wall behind her?",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","The Shroud of Turin? The lost treasure of the Incas? Lord \n      Lucan\n      ?",19,"-","No"],["TOM","A cuckoo clock!",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Oh gee. Gosh. Pass the smelling salts, I’m going to faint.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","It’s the exact same cuckoo clock Kyle Lynton brought back from last year’s toy fair in Switzerland. He put it up in his office and it drove us all mad. So he was ordered to take it home. Later on, he said he’d put it in his garage because his wife wouldn’t have it in the house.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","And who did I see sitting in front of that cuckoo clock? Cheri \n      Mahler\n       - that’s who!",19,"-","No"],["TOM","Kyle and Cheri are having an affair.",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Holy \n      shit\n      ! Are you sure?",19,"-","No"],["TOM","One hundred percent.",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","In which case, I take back my recent barrage of sarcastic though witty utterances.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","And it gets better.",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","It couldn’t possibly.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","Right in the middle of the meeting, Cheri sacked Kyle! Can you believe it?",19,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh to be a fly on the wall in that garage right now! I bet the two of them are having a right screaming match.",19,"-","No"],["TOM","Wait till I tell Freddy. He's going to piss himself!",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom dashes out the door. He can be heard running up the stairs.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Boys!",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","She turns the sound back on.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["BRODY","We've had a lot of calls from people wondering when - and indeed if - the goods they're ordering will pop through their letter box. Worry not, good people of Consumer Land. The powers that be here at the Great British Shopping Experience are on top of it.",19,"-","No"],["BRODY","We've done a deal with a certain delivery company to see to it that your goodies get through to you come Hell or High Water. No nasty little UFO's going to stop us from supplying you with yummy, scrummy stuff like this 9 carat gold bracelet with 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 real zirconium jewels which normally retails for over one hundred pounds - yes that's one zero zero smackeroonies - but which can be yours (and I think we're mad offering it at this price) for a measly thirty-six quid.",19,"-","No"],["BRODY","Yes, you heard me: thirty-six quid.",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Brody cups a hand over his ear.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["BRODY","What's that I hear? Could it be the sound of thousands of excited viewers getting on their phones and ringing the number at the bottom of this screen so they can get their hands on the bargain of the century? Yes! I do believe it is.",19,"-","No"],["BRODY","I'd be surprised if we don't sell out of these bracelets within a matter of minutes. So what are you waiting for? Phone, phone, phone - or forever regret missing out.",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara picks up her phone and speed dials the Great British Shopping Experience.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","You are through to the Great British Shopping Experience. All our lines are busy right now but if you hold, we’ll put you through to one of our operators as soon as they’re available.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Your call is very important to us. Please hold.",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the television, the Great British Shopping Channel is temporarily interrupted by a Government public information film.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From the television, comes the sound of a KLAXON.\n    ",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Attention! Attention! The following is a Government Public Service Announcement containing information that could save your life.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Please watch and listen carefully.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Earth is under attack as never before.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","The Black Knight satellite is an implacable menace, a weapon of war against which we have no defence. We must all do what we can to survive and to protect the ones we love.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Very little is known about the Black Knight. Even less is known about the deadly radiation it constantly spews onto our planet as it passes overhead. All we do know is that causes people to go mad and develop an insatiable appetite for human flesh.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","There is no hiding from this radiation. It passes through solid matter with ease and penetrates the ground for many miles. Even solid lead has proven to be no barrier.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","The Black Knight is in orbit over the equator. It circles the planet once every 23 hours and 19 minutes, making it possible to predict where it will be at any given moment. Check social media to find out when it is due to be overhead where you are. Make a note of the time that it is due. If, for some reason, you cannot access social media, remember this: the Black Knight returns every 23 hours and 19 minutes.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","As it comes closer to where you are, it will jam all radio transmissions and take over the Internet and other means of electronic media. When it does so, it broadcasts a series of bleeps on all frequencies through all media. Listen out for these bleeps. They will tell you how close the satellite is.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","The nearer the satellite is to you, the louder the bleeps are and the less time there is between each of them.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Regard the bleeps as a warning to take immediate action to protect yourself and those around you against the Black Knight.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","When the Black Knight approaches, everyone should go to a room where they must be alone. Do not share a room with anyone - no matter how much you love them, no matter how much you trust them.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","The fewer people you have within your immediate vicinity, the greater your chance of survival and the less chance there is of you becoming a flesh-eating maniac.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","If you can, restrain yourself and/or those around you. This can be done, for instance, rope, string or bed sheets.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Do not think that because you love someone, they are safe from you.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","Do not think because someone loves you, you are safe from them.",19,"-","No"],["VOICE ON PHONE","The madness inflicted by the Black Knight is immune to love and sentiment. We do not know why it only affects some and not others. The next time it passes, it might be you it affects - you it drives crazy. Then again, it may be your partner, you parent, even your child...",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living rOOM - day -",19,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara sits with her phone glued to her ear.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom enters with lunch on a tray.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["TOM","It ain’t pretty, but it’s lunch.",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara nods absently.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits next to her. Takes his plate and tea from the tray, places them on the floor at his feet. Puts the tray on Barbara’s lap.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He grabs remote.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["TOM","You mind?",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara shrugs.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom changes the channel to BBC News. Louise BATES is at the news desk.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara looks at her lunch as if wandering what the hell it is.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["BATES","And now we can go live to Phoebe Anderson on College Green by the Houses of Parliament where a small group of protesters has gathered.",20,"-","No"],["BATES","Phoebe, what can you tell us about what’s happening there?",20,"-","No"],["ANDERSON","Well, Louise, as you say and as you can see, there is a protest in progress here outside the Mother of Parliaments. It has been \n      organised\n       by a group calling themselves the League Against Disinformation - LAD for short - and I'm joined here by their leader, Russell Jackson.",20,"-","No"],["ANDERSON","Mr. Jackson, would you care to tell our viewers why you and your colleagues have gathered here today?",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Yes I would, Phoebe. We are letting the government know we are not buying into their bullshit.",20,"-","No"],["ANDERSON","And what bullshit would that be?",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","As if you didn't know! The media - especially you traitors at the BBC - know exactly what I am talking about. I am talking about this nonsense we're being fed vis-à-vis the so-called Black Knight satellite which amounts to the biggest hoax in history.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","There is no Black Knight satellite. It's all a con! A big, fat government lie!",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","You have to be an idiot to believe it. I mean, come on - an alien satellite? Little green men? The Government are lying to us and you, the media, are colluding with them in the biggest crime in human history.",20,"-","No"],["ANDERSON","So how do you explain the massive slaughter we’re witnessing day in, day out?",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Mass hysteria! For decades, successive governments have been poisoning our water supply with fluoride. And you know what fluoride does, don't you? It makes people susceptible to suggestion and it makes them placid, which is why the first thing the Nazis did when they invaded a country was lace the reservoirs with fluoride.",20,"-","No"],["ANDERSON","There’s no evidence they ever did that.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Look: the fact is that there is no Black Knight, no aliens, no death ray driving us insane. It’s all lies - and you know it.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","People, wake up! Stop being sheep. Do your own research.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Show me the dead bodies, the corpses piled high, the overflowing mortuaries, the mass burials. There aren’t any.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Oh sure, we’ve all seen the odd mutilated corpse but the fact of the matter is that the Government are taking the bodies of people who have died of natural causes and carving them up to make it look like they’ve been savagely attacked. What we are seeing here are the opening shots of a war against humanity, against civilisation, decency and freedom. And I want the government and all the despicable corporations behind this farce to know that we are on to them and we are prepared to fight.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","We the people will not be lied to any more. The revolution has begun!",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Me and these brave and wonderful people behind me are staying right where we are tonight. We will maintain a vigil from dusk to dawn and we will not run for cover nor will we tie each other up.",20,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Come back tomorrow and you'll find us still here, still alive, still standing. Because there is no Black Knight! No alien satellite making us all crazy!'",20,"-","No"],["TOM","What a nut job.",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Maybe he’s right. Maybe it is all a hoax.",20,"-","No"],["TOM","You’re not serious.",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Show me the satellite, Tom. Then tell me how any machine - alien or not - could make people turn to murder and cannibalism. Tell me how it could possibly affect the short-term memory of billions of people so they can’t remember what they just did. And tell me why there’s no recording - not a single video - of what supposedly happens when the satellite comes along. I’d like to know, Tom. You’re smart - or at least you say you are - so tell me how -",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Oh hello. Yes. The bracelet. You have some left?",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Thank goodness. It’s taken so long to get through, I was worried you might have sold out.",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I quite understand. These are difficult times.",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Exasperated, Tom switches of the television and takes his lunch out of the room.\n    ",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Yes I am. My membership number GSE3287351... That’s right. Mrs Barbara Caxton.",20,"-","No"],["BARBARA","It’s a VISA card... The long number is -",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. TOM’S OFFICE - day",20,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is at his desk, finishing off a mock-up comic panel for Butcher Baby on his iPad. It depicts Butcher Baby holding up the head of a freshly decapitated nun.\n    ",21,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His work is interrupted by a Zoom call from Cheri.\n    ",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","Hi, Tom. Just wanted to check in to see how things are coming along.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","I’ve got a fistful of panels I think you’ll like.",21,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He holds up his iPad to the camera on his PC.\n    ",21,"-","No"],["TOM","This one I’m especially proud of. I got the inspiration for it from Antonio Canova's famous statue, “Perseus with the Head of Medusa”.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","I’m loving it.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","I thought it might be funny to have him slay Sister Gabby - put the sanctimonious bitch out of our misery.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","Sounds great. Just one thing though, Tom. Why do you assume Butcher Baby's a “him”?",21,"-","No"],["TOM","Isn’t he? Or she? Or whatever?",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","It's not been decided as yet. My thinking is that we should make him/her transgender whereas Dave Ashton (dinosaur that he is) wants two versions of Butcher Baby - one male, one female. He says they can be differentiated by the colour of their chainsaws: blue for Boy Butcher Baby and pink for Girl Butcher Baby. I told him he was being unspeakably sexist but he said he didn't care because stereotyping sells dolls and I have to agree with him on that one, which is why I strongly believe transgender is the way to go.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","What do you think, Tom?",21,"-","No"],["TOM","Transgender sounds good to me. And I’ll tell you what would be a hoot, Cheri - something that will really turbo-boost our sales. How about if we gave him - or her - the ability to transition. He could start off as a boy and then at the press of a button - hey presto! - he’s a girl. Then another press and he's a boy again.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","I like it, Tom. I really do. Only I'm not sure it's feasible. I mean it would need some quite intricate machinery to turn its penis into a vagina and back again.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","I was thinking more along the lines of a detachable penis.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","Are you kidding me? That's the dumbest idea I've heard in a long time. You can't put a detachable penis on a child's toy.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","I don’t see why not.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","Two words, Tom: choking hazard!",21,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh yeah. I hadn’t thought of that.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","If you can get those panels over to me this evening, that would be great. Otherwise tomorrow morning will do. In the meantime, I'm e-mailing you a couple of designs I want you to keep under your hat for now.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","For Butcher Baby?",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","For Butcher Baby's friends. If Butcher Baby sells as well as you and I both know it will, then we'll follow up with a range of complementary dolls. Barbie has Ken. Sindy has Paul. And Butcher Baby will have Psycho Sam and Man-Hater Mandy. What do you think?",21,"-","No"],["TOM","Genius, Cheri. Utter fucking genius.",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","Isn’t it?",21,"-","No"],["CHERI","By the way, Tom, I've decided to reinstate Kyle. He may be a \n      dick\n      , but for the sake of the project, we need him aboard. I hope you understand.",21,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh sure, Cheri. I understand all right.",21,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - NIGHT",21,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom enters. Swigs at the whisky. Picks up and turns on the transistor radio.\n    ",22,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes out to -\n    ",22,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. back GARDEN - night - continuous",22,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom locks the kitchen door and heads straight to the shed. Along the way, the radio starts \n      bleeping\n      .\n    ",23,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP... BLEEP... BLEEP...\n    ",23,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Shed - NIGHT - continuous",23,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In the shed, Tom lies on the mattress, transistor radio in hand, and nervously awaits the coming of the Black Knight.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The radio starts to BLEEP.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The bleeps grow louder and louder, more and more urgent.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...! BLEEP...! BLEEP...!\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sweats. Fights to control his terror.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEP!\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Green light fills the shed.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom convulses. Opens his mouth to scream.\n    ",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLACKOUT:",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. back GARDEN - NIGHT",24,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FADE IN.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The Black Knight has just this moment passed by. We are outside its influence.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A green glow on the horizon thins then vanishes.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As suburbia surfaces from its fugue, dogs BARK. CAR and BURGLAR ALARMS sound. Lights go on in nearby houses.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, bedraggled and befuddled, stumbles out of his shed.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He stands in the middle of the garden, looking up at the Milky Way, displaying a gamut of emotions - awe, loathing, fear...\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Distant GUN SHOTS bring him back to earth.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He unlocks the kitchen door.\n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes into - \n    ",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - NIGHT - coNTINUOUS",25,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom takes a swig of whisky.\n    ",26,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes out to -\n    ",26,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. HallWAY - NIGHT - conTINUOUS",26,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom checks the front door and table then hurries up the stairs to -\n    ",27,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Landing - NIGHT - conTINUOUS",27,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom unlocks the bedroom door.\n    ",28,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Enters -\n    ",28,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. BEDROOM - NIGHT - coNTINUOUS",28,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As Tom comes in, Barbara (tied up as usual) eyes him warily.\n    ",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","If you’ve come to eat my liver, I’m afraid we’re all out of onions. You’ll have to make do with fava beans.",29,"-","No"],["TOM","That’s not funny.",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Wasn’t supposed to be. What time is it?",29,"-","No"],["TOM","About 3 o’clock.",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","At night?",29,"-","No"],["TOM","The Black Knight's not long since gone. Would you like me to untie you?",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","No. I would like you to leave me trussed up so I can spend a delightful few hours pretending to be a Christmas turkey.",29,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh. OK.",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","You get back here, Tom Caxton, or I’ll rip your bollocks off.",29,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom makes a start on untying Barbara.\n    ",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","How’s that little soldier, of yours?",29,"-","No"],["TOM","Pumped up and ready for action, ma’am.",29,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Good. Because as soon as I get my circulation back, I’m going to want a right good seeing to.",29,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LiVING ROOM - night",29,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara are watching the television from the sofa.\n    ",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Louise Bates is presenting.\n    ",30,"-","No"],["BATES","These pictures appear to show a Saturn V rocket about to be launched from Cape Canaveral.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","And I’m just hearing that the White House have confirmed that at approximately 9 P.M. Eastern Daylight Time - that's 1 A.M. GMT - NASA launched a Saturn V from Cape Canaveral but have so far declined to give any reason for doing so.",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","ON TELEVISION: Night time launch of a Saturn V with commentary from NASA Ground Control.\n    ",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","We follow the launch to just before the picture cuts to the watching crowd.\n    ",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Our science correspondent Professor Leonid Volkov from the University of Essex has joined us online to talk about this astonishing development. First of all, where the hell did the Americans get a fully functioning Saturn V rocket from?",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On television: CAMERA cuts to Leonid Volkov\n    ",30,"-","No"],["VOLKOV","That is the 64 million dollar question and I don't really have an answer, Louise. When the Apollo moon program came to its untimely end, the Americans had built a total of 16 Saturn \n      Vs\n      , 13 of which were launched into space. The remaining three were distributed to various museums. Having said that, clearly there must have been at least one more Saturn V which for reasons I find hard to fathom was kept secret from the public. Unlike the three museum pieces, the American government must have spent millions every year for more than half a century keeping it in workable condition and now they bring it out of mothballs and shoot it into space. Seems crazy to me.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Yes, it is hard to make sense of. Clearly, this has something to do with the Black Knight satellite.",30,"-","No"],["VOLKOV","That would be the obvious conclusion.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Is it possible that its payload is some sort of top secret weapon which they believe can put paid to the Black Knight?",30,"-","No"],["VOLKOV","Da, it's possible but who can say? And even if it is a weapon, there is no guarantee that it will be effective. Remember, we have thrown several \n      gigatons\n       of atomic warheads at this beast and what good has it done? We might as well be using bows and arrows.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Well, let's hope you're wrong, Professor.",30,"-","No"],["VOLKOV","Da. Let’s hope.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Professor Leonid Volkov, thank you for your time.",30,"-","No"],["VOLKOV","Whatever.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","And now we're going live by news drone to College Green and viewers are warned that this report will contain graphic images that some might find deeply upsetting.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","As you can see, there's Big Ben in the background and beyond that the River Thames. Now the drone is descending towards College Green, using its spotlight to pick out the grisly details of the grim tragedy that unfolded there tonight.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","You may recall that a group calling themselves the League Against Deception had assembled on the green to protest against an alleged conspiracy. Their leader, Russell Jackson, told our reporter that he and his followers believed the Black Knight phenomenon to be a hoax and they intended to prove it by ignoring official advice and staying on the green during tonight’s transit.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","And this is the result: dead bodies everywhere. So far, we've counted a dozen but there are probably more - not to mention a number of walking wounded.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","As we get up close on this dead protestor here, you can see his face frozen in a look of abject terror. And next to him is someone who's been disembowelled and it looks like a good deal of their intestines have been eaten.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","None of the dead have been identified as yet. Those blue flashing lights are from a couple of police cars and an ambulance that have just arrived on the scene.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Russell Jackson, the group’s leader, is not believed to be amongst those who lost their lives in what was a quite avoidable tragedy. We hope to catch up with him as soon as possible to get his reaction to this bloody mess, which - let's face it - is by and large his fault. It would be interesting to see if he's changed his mind about the Black Knight being a hoax.",30,"-","No"],["BATES","Incidentally, those things moving about on the edge of the picture are rats enjoying a breakfast of freshly-served human flesh.",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. Back garden - day",30,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits himself on the patio with a bar of chocolate which he bites into now and then. He takes out his transistor radio and switches it on. Tunes to Galaxy Talk Radio and the Ken TATE Phone-In Show.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON is shooting his mouth off.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","All I'm saying is that it's nonsense to say that the Black Knight was sent by God to punish the gays.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","Amen to that.",31,"-","No"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","I mean it's not as if there's anything new about men doing disgusting things with other men. That sort of thing goes back to the ancient Greeks. God didn't much mind it back then, so why should he mind it now?",31,"-","No"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","No, what's changed, James, is the way certain people are making a mockery of God by claiming there are more than two genders despite what the Bible says.",31,"-","No"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","Even when the \n      Sodomites\n      , the \n      pedos\n       and the commies were doing their worst, God was more than happy to leave us alone - apart from the odd earthquake or tsunami to punish the atheists - but with men claiming to be women and women acting like they were born with penises, is it any wonder he's mad at us?",31,"-","No"],["BOB FROM WOLVERHAMPTON","I'm willing to bet, James, that everyone who's died because of the Black Knight is transgendered - in thought if not in deed.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","OK, Bob. I've run out of tin foil so I'm going to have to cut you off there.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","That was Bob from Wolverhampton. Keep taking the pills, Bob.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","And ne \n      xt\n       on the line is Katie, a housewife from Blackpool, Lancashire.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","Go ahead, Katie. You have the ears of the nation.",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL gets to have her say.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","Thank you, Ken. I just wanted to ask why it is that with thousands  of nuclear weapons in the world - all those rockets and missiles that have cost us billions and billions of pounds - we haven’t been able to shoot down the Black Knight. We keep hearing all sorts of excuses but they all sound ridiculous to me.",31,"-","No"],["TATE","Well, Katie, according to the governments of both the United States and Russia, numerous attempts have been made to nuke the satellite but to no avail.",31,"-","No"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","And do you believe that \n      crap\n      ? These are nuclear weapons we’re talking about. Some of them are supposedly powerful enough to totally destroy a city as big as London and yet they can’t destroy something not much bigger than a family car?",31,"-","No"],["TATE","The problem is that the Black Knight is not exactly defenceless. It appears to be surrounded by a forcefield which causes missiles to self-destruct while they’re too far away from the satellite to damage it.",31,"-","No"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","But they’re nukes! We’re told they get to within a quarter of a mile of the Black Knight before they go off. That’s got to be close enough, hasn’t it?",31,"-","No"],["TATE","Let me finish, Katie. Outer space isn’t London or Hiroshima or Bikini Atoll. As I understand it, most of the damage done by nuclear weapons comes from the blast wave. In space, where there’s no atmosphere, you don’t get a blast wave, which means for a nuke to be of any use against the Black Knight it has to explode right in its face, as it were.",31,"-","No"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","Well, lasers then. What about lasers?",31,"-","No"],["TATE","What about them?",31,"-","No"],["KATIE FROM BLACKPOOL","Ronald Reagan promised the U.S. \n      would\n       build lasers powerful enough to punch holes in the moon. That was over fifty years ago. So where are these lasers and why aren’t they using them?",31,"-","No"],["TATE","To be honest with you, Katie, that’s a question I can’t give a good answer to. If any of my listeners out there are privy to American military secrets, perhaps you could give us a call. The number to ring is -",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom turns off the radio.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He spits out a half-chewed piece of chocolate. It lands on the lawn. He watches in grim fascination as it is mobbed by ants.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. TOM’S OFFICE - DAY\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, his mood gloomy, enters and slumps into his chair.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His phone rings. He answers.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["TOM","Tom Caxton.",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the other end of the line is ISABELLE Lynton.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Mr. Caxton, you probably don’t remember me though we did meet once. I’m Isabelle Lynton.",31,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh yes. Kyle’s wife.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Would you like a good laugh, Mr. Caxton?",31,"-","No"],["TOM","I can't imagine there's anything can make me laugh right now, but you're welcome to try.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","It’s about my husband. As you know, the man’s a complete and utter \n      shit\n       with the morals of a warthog on heat. A couple of days ago, I caught him in bed with your boss, Cheri \n      Mahler\n      .",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I’ve always known about his philandering and I’ve tolerated it - not liked it, mind; just tolerated it - so long as he gave me every opportunity to pretend it wasn’t happening. But this was my bed he was fucking his whore in. My bed in my house right next to the room where my children sleep!",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I’ll spare you the details of what I said to him and his tart and skip to the part where I packed my bags, picked up my kids from school and skedaddled off to my parents.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","And if you’re thinking, “this isn’t very funny. When are you going to make me laugh like you promised, Mrs. Lynton?”, hang on to your hat because here it comes.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Last night, just after the Black Knight had been and gone, I got a phone call. When I saw it was from Kyle, I nearly didn’t answer, but curiosity got the better of me and I’m glad it did - and when I say glad, I mean ecstatic. There’s no sweeter sound, Mr. Caxton, than the sound of a philandering husband screeching like a little girl being force-fed worms.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","My penis!\n       \n      he\n       screamed. \n      My penis, my penis, my penis! The bitch has bitten off my penis!",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Isabelle cracks up with laughter, sounding more hysterical with each passing second.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is appalled.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","My penis!",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom smiles.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","She’s got my penis in her mouth!",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In spite of himself, Tom chuckles.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Oh my God! She’s chewing it!",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Isabelle cackles. It is too much for Tom. He joins in.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Great big belly laughs. Tears streaming down his cheeks.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","And now she’s choking!",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The two laugh uncontrollably until their mirth runs its course.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","They catch their breath.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I’m calling from the hospital. They’ve had to incinerate what little of Kyle’s penis Cheri left him. Apparently they can grow him a new one - isn’t science wonderful? - but there’s been such a spate of men having their dicks bitten off he’s going to have to wait at least three years, by which time I’ll be a happy divorcee.",31,"-","No"],["TOM","Thank you for sharing that with me, Mrs. Lynton. It was just the tonic I needed. But I’m curious as to why you chose me of all people to share your good news with.",31,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Don’t flatter yourself, Mr. Caxton. Your name just happened to be on Kyle’s mobile phone. I plan to spend the next few hours going through his contact list, letting everyone and his brother know that my husband no longer has a penis.",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Isabelle cuts the connection.\n    ",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",31,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara, as usual, is glued to the Great British Shopping Experience.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["BRODY","Quick, quick, quick, folks, because this one is definitely going to sell out in a flash. He who hesitates has lost the bargain of a lifetime.",32,"-","No"],["BRODY","“Well, what is it, Dan?” I hear you say. “Tell us, you incredibly charismatic television person, you.”",32,"-","No"],["BRODY","It is - drum roll - a straightjacket - perfect for restraining that special someone in your life.",32,"-","No"],["BRODY","And I’ve just had a voice in my ear telling me we have to break for a news flash - something we’ve never before had to do here at the Great British Shopping Experience Channel. It better be bloody important, else I’m going to very cross!",32,"-","No"],["BRODY","Don’t go away. We’ll be right back.",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Television cuts to a screen with the following message:\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","An important announcement from the Prime Minister for every inhabitant of the United Kingdom will follow shortly.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","This announcement is to be broadcast on all available channels.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Stay tuned.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The picture cuts to Prime Minister Arthur CAVELL, sat at a desk in a well-appointed office.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","CAPTION on the television: \n      The Right Honourable Arthur Cavell, Prime Minister \n    ",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","My fellow citizens, as none of you can fail to be aware, this nation, along with every other nation across every continent, is facing an unprecedented crisis, the enormity of which cannot be overstated.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","Five days ago, something strange began to happen and is continuing to happen, causing each and every one of us to black out at regular intervals and in many cases commit horrendous acts of murder and cannibalism.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","The source of this phenomenon has been pinpointed. It is a satellite of unknown origin, design and purpose commonly known as the Black Knight.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","Numerous attempts to bring down this vile artefact have failed and so the killings go on and will go on for the foreseeable future.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","In these desperate times, desperate remedies are called for and it is therefore my unpleasant duty to announce the immediate commencement of martial law in the United Kingdom along with a 24 hour curfew. All civilians are hereby ordered to remain indoors unless specifically exempted. Any breech of this order will be considered High Treason and punishable by death. The army and police now have the authority to use lethal force as they see fit.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","Let me make this clear. Unless you have been told otherwise, you must not venture out of doors. Anyone doing so is liable to summary execution. There are no exceptions.",32,"-","No"],["CAVELL","This is total lockdown. Stay indoors or suffer the consequences!",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Stunned, Tom switches off the television. Sits shaking his head.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Tom?",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Yes?",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I tried to order some earrings.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","What?",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Beautiful earrings with cultured pearls.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Earrings? Did you not just hear the Prime Minister declare martial law?",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I tried to buy a pair. The transaction was declined. It’s your credit card. I think it’s \n      maxed\n       out.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Hardly surprising the way you’ve been spending.",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Ring them, will you, Tom?",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Ring who?",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","The credit card company. Ask them to increase your credit limit.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","You have got to be shitting me, Barbara. Don’t you understand? Don’t you get what’s happening?",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","It can’t harm to ask.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","There’s nobody to ask. You saw me yesterday trying to call the bank. No answer. You saw me trying to call the gas company. No answer. I tried to call my mother, the police, even the fucking Samaritans. No fucking answer! About the only people answering their phones is that \n      shitty\n       shopping channel you’re always fucking glued to!",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","There’s no need to swear. I don’t know what you’re getting upset about. If they say no then no it is. I’ll dip into my savings.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","You call them. The number’s on the phone. I bet you won’t have to wait five seconds to get through. I bet straightaway they’ll say “Oh sure we’ll increase your husband’s credit limit. How much would you like? Ten thousand pounds? A hundred thousand? How about a million fucking quid!’",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Tom, stop it. You’re scaring me.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","I’m scaring you? Me? We’re in the middle of a cannibal apocalypse and the thing you’re scared off is me? Your own fucking husband?",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara breaks down. Buries her face in her hands.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Stop it! Please stop it. I just want to buy something nice before I die. Is that too much to ask?",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom relents. His anger is spent.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["TOM","You’re not going to die. I won’t let it happen.",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","You’re going to kill me, Tom. I know you are. And if you don’t kill me, I’ll kill you because that’s the way it is. People are killing the people they love and there’s no way to stop it.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","They’ll find a way.",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","But they won’t, will they?",32,"-","No"],["TOM","I don’t know.",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Yes, you do, Tom. You know full well where this is heading. Stop lying.",32,"-","No"],["TOM","I’m not lying.",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara shoves Tom.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Liar! You’re a bloody liar, Tom Caxton. We’re going to die! You know we’re going to die! Just admit it, can’t you?",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Pack it in, Barbara.",32,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Say it, Tom. Say we’re going to die - you, me and every human being on this planet. We’re going to die, we’re going to die, we’re going to die!",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom slaps Barbara.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Stop it!",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, realising what he’s done, is appalled at himself.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["TOM","Barbara, I’m sorry. I’m just so -",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara gleefully throws herself on Tom. There is something feral about her as she ravishes him, pulling his hair, kissing him fiercely.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","At first, Tom is paralysed with confusion. It is only when Barbara viciously bites his ear that he responds with animal passion.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara wrestle. Hands all over each other. Tearing at each other’s clothing.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","They make love with wild abandon.\n    ",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. living room - later",32,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara at the table playing Monopoly. Their faces display signs of their bout of rough sex.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The television is on, displaying a notice: \n    ",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The Great British Shopping Experience is temporarily off-air. We will be back as soon as possible.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","We’re almost out of food.",33,"-","No"],["TOM","I think the Keplers are dead.",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Who?",33,"-","No"],["TOM","The people next door. Mr. \n      and\n       Mrs. Kepler. The old couple.",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","So that’s their name? Kepler. I never knew that.",33,"-","No"],["TOM","I’ll try their house when it gets dark.",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","They’re not likely to have much food - what with them being old and all that.",33,"-","No"],["TOM","They’ll have some. It’ll have to do for now.",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","What if they’re not dead?",33,"-","No"],["TOM","I’m sure they are. No harm checking.",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara lands on Chance. She takes a Chance card.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Get out of jail free. Well, ain’t I the lucky one?",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The \n      GBSE\n       Channel comes back on air.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","Hello? Is anybody there? This is Dan Brody coming to you live from the studios of \n      GBSE\n      , the Great British Shopping Experience Channel. As you’ve no doubt gathered, we’ve been off the air for a little while but now we’re back and we aim to go on broadcasting and bringing you fantastic bargains for as long as we possibly can.",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","So let’s not hang about shall we? We’ve got a lot of shopping to catch up on.",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","Those who were watching when we were so rudely interrupted will recall this delightful porcelain poodle imported all the way from Taiwan. We said it was worth £89 but you could have it for a mere 39 quid. Well, bollocks to that. Who’ll give me 29 quid?",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","No, let’s make it a fiver. Five fucking quid for the finest fucking porcelain poodle money can fucking buy. Lovingly handcrafted by pre-pubescent slaves in some oriental sweat shop. Actually, like everything else we flog here, it’s a pile of \n      crap\n       but that’s not going to stop you buying it, is it, you fucking morons?",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","There’s the number to call at the bottom of the screen. Let’s show the aliens it’s going to take more than an apocalypse to dampen our rampant consumerism.",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","By the way, in case you’re wondering what’s happened to the delightful Lorna \n      McReady\n       who usually fills this slot, she’s no longer with us. One of the camera crew had her kidneys for breakfast. Such a sweet girl. I bet she tasted delicious.",33,"-","No"],["BRODY","We’ve yet to deter -",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A power cut renders the telly inactive.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Outside, BURGLAR ALARMS go off.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A HELICOPTER passes overhead.\n    ",33,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh well. Nearly time for bed anyway.",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. BEDROOM - NIGHT",33,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom ties up Barbara. Beds her up for the night.\n    ",34,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. Garden - night",34,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","With his transistor radio \n      BLEEPING\n      , Tom hurries into -\n    ",35,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Shed - night - conTINUOUS",35,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Terrified, Tom barely has time to throw himself onto the mattress before the \n      BLEEPs\n       become one CONTINUOUS BLEEP and the shed fills with green light.\n    ",36,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Agony!\n    ",36,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLACKOUT:",36,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","ext. Garden - day",36,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom - haggard, drained - emerges from the shed.\n    ",37,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He washes his face at the garden tap. Drinks.\n    ",37,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Inspects the ant nest.\n    ",37,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes indoors.\n    ",37,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",37,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara, both wearing red tracksuits, are watching television.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Louise Bates is presenting.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["BATES","We're joining our reporter, Phoebe Anderson who has tracked down the conspiracy theorist Russell Jackson, leader of the League Against Disinformation. As you may have seen yesterday, the League held a demonstration on College Green and stayed out all night in an attempt to prove that the Black Knight is a hoax. Many of those demonstrators are now dead, having been attacked and devoured by their fellow protesters.",38,"-","No"],["BATES","Phoebe, is that Mr. Jackson sitting in those bushes behind you?'",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Yes it is, Louise. I've cornered him here in a very deserted Hyde Park. If you listen, you'll hear something that's not been heard at this time of day in central London for hundreds of years - no traffic, no people. Here, at least, the curfew is being observed. I and Tim, my cameraman, by the way, have a special press permit which allows us to be out and about without the risk of getting shot.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","These two handsome gentlemen are Sergeants Wycliffe and Moore, an escort provided by the army for my protection.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Can we get the camera on Mr. Jackson, please?",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","There, in the bushes, looking forlorn and somewhat manic is Russell Jackson, the man who yesterday assured us as to the non-existence of the Black Knight satellite.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","I'm not getting any closer because last time I tried, he bit my leg.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Mr. Jackson! Can you hear me? I was wondering if you'd care to share your current thoughts regarding the Black Knight satellite? Do you still insist the worldwide phenomenon that has killed millions of people and driven millions more into insanity is down to the infernal machinations of a sinister cabal out to destroy civilisation?",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Vague \n      mumblings\n       from Jackson can be heard but not deciphered.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","I'm sorry, Mr. Jackson. You'll have to speak up if you want to be heard.",38,"-","No"],["JACKSON","I said damn you! You whore of Satan! I hope you burn in Hell for eternity along with all the other shit stains at the BBC.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Can you remember, Mr. Jackson, who you killed last night? Whose flesh you feasted upon? Whose blood you drank? Because that’s what happened, isn’t it? The Black Knight came and turned you into a homicidal maniac. You’ve blood on your hands, Mr. Jackson - quite literally.",38,"-","No"],["JACKSON","Whore! Slut! Slag! Cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt, cunt! You cunting fucking cunt!",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","You can't see it at home because Tim has quite rightly turned his camera away, but Mr. Jackson is now defecating on the footpath.",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Mr. Jackson, aren't you ashamed of yourself?",38,"-","No"],["JACKSON","I hope your children die of cancer, you cunt-whore!",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Mr. Jackson, I have been asked by Sergeant Wycliffe and Sergeant Moore to inform you that you are in breach of the lockdown. As you may or may not know, the penalty for that is death.",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","We hear TWO RIFLES BEING COCKED.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["PHOEBE","Goodbye, Mr. Jackson.",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","TWO SHOTS ring out.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom turns off the television.\n    ",38,"-","No"],["TOM","I don’t know whether to laugh or to cry.",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Tom’s office - day",38,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom logs into the morning conference. FREDDY is the only other participant.\n    ",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Tom! So glad you made it. I thought maybe I was going to be all on my lonesome here.",39,"-","No"],["TOM","I take it you’ve heard about Cheri and Kyle?",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","If it wasn't so funny, it would be tragic. Once this Black Knight bollocks is over, I intend to make a film about it. I was thinking Ana de \n      Armas\n       might make a good Cheri.",39,"-","No"],["TOM","Might I suggest Kenneth \n      Branagh\n       for Kyle?",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","You might indeed. Now then, are we going to bother  with this meeting? Or shall we just call it a - No, wait! Cheri's dialling in.",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Morning, Cheri.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Sorry I'm late. I've had a bit of a domestic situation to deal with.",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Nothing too serious I hope?",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Nothing I couldn't handle.",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Kyle's not with us yet. I expect he'll be along later.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Knock it off, Freddy. I can tell by your smug expression you know what happened. I suppose Kyle’s bitch of a wife told you?",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","She gave me a blow-by-blow account.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","And you, Tom? Did she call you as well?",39,"-","No"],["TOM","Now let me think? Oh yes. She rang me up and said something about you mistaking Kyle’s penis for a hotdog sausage.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Let me make one thing clear, gentlemen. What happened last night is between me and Kyle. It's not a work matter and I expect you two to act in a professional manner.",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","Oh we will, Cheri? Won’t we, Tom?",39,"-","No"],["TOM","You know me. Professional’s my middle name.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Good. First order of business: our new doll, Man-Hating Mandy. I've sent both of you the specs. Have you had a chance to look at them yet?",39,"-","No"],["TOM","Not yet. I've only just finished untying my wife.",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","I had a quick \n      shufti\n      . Just one question.",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Yes?",39,"-","No"],["FREDDY","What does a human penis taste like?",39,"-","No"],["CHERI","Well done, Freddy. You've just got yourself fired.",39,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",39,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara are at the dining table playing \n      Cluedo\n      .\n    ",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","When things get back to normal, we should put our heads together and design a board game.",40,"-","No"],["TOM","And what would this board game be about?",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Zombies. Thanks to the Black Knight, there’s going to be a whole lot of interest in that sort of thing.",40,"-","No"],["TOM","A bit morbid but I think you’re spot on. Remind me to tell you about Butcher Baby some time.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Picture this, Tom: a graveyard. It’ll be a bit like a Monopoly board but instead of streets and stations it’ll have graves and mausoleums and right in the middle would be a church. If you make it to the church, you’re safe, otherwise the zombies will be able to get you, suck out your brains and turn you into one of the living dead.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Now, if you land on a grave that hasn’t been dug up and you have the right spell, bag yourself a corpse and create your own zombie.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Then whoever has the most zombies when the sun comes up wins.",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom rolls the dice.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["TOM","Eight. That brings me to the Library.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","If one of your zombies lands on a square occupied by an opponent’s zombie, then the two zombies have to fight. Whoever rolls the highest number gets to suck out the other zombie’s brains.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","And now I think of it, we could throw in vampires and werewolves.",40,"-","No"],["TOM","It’s your go, Barbara.",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","What do you think though, Tom? I reckon we could make a killing - if you’ll pardon the expression.",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Before Tom can answer, he is interrupted by a medley of noises coming from the road outside. Unseen by us, a man named MILLER is being chased by soldiers.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","We hear:\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The CLANKING, CHURNING, WHIRLING of an armoured vehicle.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","RUNNING FEET\n    ",40,"-","No"],["SOLDIER","Stop or we’ll shoot!",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","More RUNNING FEET. Perhaps a dozen men. Coming closer.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The FRONT GATE swinging open.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["SOLDIER","Stop or we’ll shoot!",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","POUNDING on the front door.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["MILLER","Let me in! In God’s name, let me in!",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","MACHINE GUN FIRE\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Bullets TEARING INTO THE FRONT DOOR. Wood SPLINTERING. \n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FEET RUNNING up the garden path.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Motioning for Barbara to stay put, Tom goes to the window, pressing himself against the wall.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Soldiers?",40,"-","No"],["TOM","And an armoured car. There’s a dead man in the driveway. They’re dragging him away.",40,"-","No"],["TOM","Straight through the hydrangeas! Thanks a bundle.",40,"-","No"],["SERGEANT","Stay away from that window and do not come outside or you will be shot! You will not be warned again!",40,"-","No"],["TOM","Jesus!",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Startled, Tom hastily backs away from the window. Trips. Falls on the floor.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara ducks and joins him.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["BARBARA","What the actual fuck? This is suburbia. People don’t get shot in suburbia!",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","They are both silent as they listen to the armoured vehicle and the soldiers heading off down the street.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When peace returns, they take their places at the table.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom picks up the dice.\n    ",40,"-","No"],["TOM","Is it your go or mine?",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living ROOM - night",40,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the settee, Tom and Barbara are devouring a light supper of biscuits and cocoa.\n    ",41,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The television is tuned to the \n      GBSE\n       Channel.\n    ",41,"-","No"],["BRODY","OK folks. That’s got to be it for now. The Black Knight satellite is due overhead pretty soon. We here at the Great Shopping Experience Channel are off to separate rooms with as many of us locked safely away as possible and I suggest you folks out there in Consumer Land do the same.",41,"-","No"],["BRODY","Who knows? Maybe just for once we’ll all survive.",41,"-","No"],["BRODY","And in this time of perdition and uncertainty, let us pray the madness ends soon. I don't know what was in that Saturn V but something tells me it's going to put a stop to the Black Knight and its evil, evil ways.",41,"-","No"],["BRODY","Good night and God bless. See you all at 6 a.m. \n      sharp\n      .",41,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","\nThe screen goes to the ‘off-air’ sign.\n    ",41,"-","No"],["TOM","Colonel Peacock in the Library with the candlestick.",41,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Cobblers.",41,"-","No"],["TOM","I'm telling you, it was Colonel Peacock in the library with the candlestick. Kindly go check.",41,"-","No"],["TOM","Can’t it wait until the morning?",41,"-","No"],["TOM","And give you a chance to change what’s in the envelope? I don’t think so.",41,"-","No"],["TOM","You’re forgetting I’ll be tied up.",41,"-","No"],["TOM","All the same.",41,"-","No"],["TOM","Fine. I'll go get the envelope. And as I do so, I hope you notice I'm flouncing in disgust at your vile insinuation that I would stoop so low as to cheat at board games.",41,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara flounces to the table. Snatches the solution envelope. Opens it. Looks at the cards.\n    ",41,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Colonel Mustard! Billiard Room! Candlestick! You weren’t even close.",41,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Oh well. You can’t win ‘em all.",41,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Bedroom - night",41,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is about to tie Barbara up.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","No.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","No?",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Get into bed with me, Tom.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","That’s not safe.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Do you think I don’t trust my own husband not to kill me?",42,"-","No"],["TOM","There exists a distinct possibility that I might just do that.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Or are you afraid you might wake up to find me sucking your brains out through a straw?",42,"-","No"],["TOM","Frankly - yes.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Listen, that satellite is going to keep orbiting the earth, spewing its poisonous radiation until every last one of us is dead. And if it doesn’t kill us all, what then? We’ll be living in a world of trauma and guilt - a world where there’s barely a man, woman or child who hasn’t killed someone they love and eaten human flesh.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I don’t want to live in that world.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Now get into this bed and do what a husband’s supposed to do. I’ve had enough of you slinking off to that fucking shed of yours.",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Knowing when he’s beaten, Tom climbs into bed with Barbara. He turns on his transistor radio which spews out static.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["TOM","If I kill you, I’ll kill myself.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","That’s the spirit, Tom.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","Tomorrow, I’ll get us some food from next door. I’m sure the Keplers are dead. And if they’re not, I’ll try some of the other houses.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I’ll come with you.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","Too dangerous.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","So what isn’t right now? If you’re going to get shot for looting, I’m going to get shot with you. And no arguments.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","We’ll see what happens.",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara takes Tom’s arm. Wraps it around herself.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Tell me about Cheri \n      Mahler\n      .",42,"-","No"],["TOM","What about her?",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","Is she insane? I mean, to bite off a man’s penis and then act as if it hadn’t happened... she can’t be right in the head.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","I think she was in shock, that’s all. Right now, she’s probably having a fit of the screaming ab dabs.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","You fancy her.",42,"-","No"],["TOM","Do not.",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","When I mentioned her name, I felt your penis twitch.",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The radio starts to BLEEP.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["TOM","Hell’s bells! The kitchen door. I’ve left it unlocked.",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom starts to rise. Barbara restrains him.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["BARBARA","I need you here.",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As the \n      BLEEPING\n       intensifies, Tom and Barbara hold onto each other. They are terrified.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The bleeps run into one another - \n      BLEEEEEEEEEEEEP\n      ! The room fills with green light.\n    ",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara open their mouths to scream but before any sound comes out -\n    ",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLACKOUT:",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. BeDROOM - night - later",42,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FADE IN:",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The Black Knight has passed. Tom and Barbara are next to each other in bed.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In the corner sits MR. KEPLER, Tom’s elderly next door neighbour. He has bits of human flesh smeared down the front of his chest and one of Barbara’s ears in his hand.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom opens his eyes. Stares at the ceiling as he gets his bearings.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He has a bad feeling. Turns towards Barbara to find that half her face is missing.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","She is quite dead.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom convulses. His arms, jerking like they've received a jolt of electricity, push him away from Barbara, out of the bed, against the wall, knocking the wind from him.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Effortlessly, he vomits, spilling the contents of his stomach down his chin.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Shock has left him shaking and all but catatonic.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From the corner of the room, comes the small voice of Mr. Kepler.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["MR. KEPLER","I’m sorry.",43,"-","No"],["TOM","What?",43,"-","No"],["MR. KEPLER","I’m sorry, I’m sorry, I’m sorry.",43,"-","No"],["TOM","Too late for sorry. Sorry doesn’t cut it.",43,"-","No"],["MR. KEPLER","I couldn’t help myself.",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Only now does Tom realise the voice isn’t in his head. He looks across the room at Mr. Kepler.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["MR. KEPLER","It was the Black Knight. I went to bed with Mrs. Kepler. I woke up. There was meat in my mouth. Human flesh, all salty and sour.",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A sudden rage grips Tom. Screaming, he launches himself at Mr. Kepler. Drives his fist into the old man’s face.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Mr. Kepler does not resist. Sits there passively as Tom lays into him again and again. There is even a smile on his face when Tom throttles him. \n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom continues to grip Mr. Kepler’s throat for some seconds after the old man has expired. \n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When he finally lets go, he crawls on his knees to the side of the bed and strokes Barbara’s hair.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["TOM","It wasn’t me, Barbara. It was old Mr. Kepler. There was nothing I could do. You understand, don’t you, Barbara?",43,"-","No"],["TOM","Here, I’ll tell you what? How about you and me going downstairs and watching the Great British Shopping Experience? We can use my company credit card. Let’s get that cruet set you wanted.",43,"-","No"],["TOM","And maybe some Harry Potter slippers. Remember, you were thinking about getting them but thought it might be a bit childish? Well, bollocks to that. If you want Harry Potter slippers, then Harry Potter slippers you shall have.",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom stands. Gently lifts Barbara from the bed. Carries her to the door.\n    ",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. Tom’s office - day",43,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is watching a government-sponsored video on \n      YouTube\n      .\n    ",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Under no circumstances must you go outside, not even to bury a corpse.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","If you have a corpse in your home or other secure place, put it in a body bag or wrap it securely in several layers of sheets, curtains, canvas and whatever other material comes to hand. Bind this covering with any of the following:",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Parcel tape",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Duct tape",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Wiring (e.g. \n      computer\n       power cable)",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","String",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Rope",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Twine",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Etc…",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","If you have a freezer large enough to accommodate the corpse, place it in there. Otherwise store the corpse in a dry, dark place much as you would if it was food.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Thoroughly sanitise all areas and items that have been in contact with the corpse.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Always wash your hands after handling cadavers.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Do not leave the corpse outside, whether in your garden or out in the road.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","Keep dead bodies away from children and pets.",44,"-","No"],["YOUTUBE VOICEOVER","For other tips on dealing with a corpse inside your home, look in the comments section below. And if you found this video interesting, smash that like button!",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sets about wrapping Mr. Kepler’s body as per the instructions above. As he does so, he seems strangely content.\n    ",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He wraps Mr. Kepler in bed sheets and curtains then binds him with parcel tape.\n    ",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When he is done -\n    ",44,"-","No"],["TOM","And here’s one I prepared earlier!",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom picks up Mr. Kepler and throws him over his shoulder. He goes out to -\n    ",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Landing - day - conTINUOUS",44,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","- then downstairs to -\n    ",45,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Hallway - day - contiNUOUS",45,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","- and into -\n    ",46,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LiVING ROOM - DAY - continuous",46,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara has been propped up on the settee. She is ‘watching’ a public information film regarding the Black Knight.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom looks around for somewhere to put Mr. Kepler. Eventually puts him in the corner. He then sits next to Barbara.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["TOM","What’s this then? More government propaganda? They must think we’re right mugs. Why don’t they put on something cheerful like Tom and Jerry cartoons? Or Lady and the Tramp? God, I love that film. You know that bit where they’re eating spaghetti?",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom mutes the television.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara topples against Tom.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom gently takes hold of Barbara and manoeuvres her into an upright position and places her elbow on the arm of the settee.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["TOM","Things are going to be a lot easier once rigor mortis sets in.",47,"-","No"],["TOM","Did I tell you Mr. Kepler called today? I was right you know - about him being dead, only he wasn't dead when I said it but he is dead now. So now we won't have to put up with Bach at 6 in the morning any more. Every cloud and all that.",47,"-","No"],["TOM","Now let's look at this face of yours.",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom inspects Barbara’s ruined face, touching it delicately with his finger tips.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["TOM","You never did look your best first thing in the morning, did you? Now let’s see what I can do.",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From the sideboard, Tom fetches Barbara’s sewing kit. He takes out the scissors from it and trims away ragged bits of flesh and hanging skin.\n    ",47,"-","No"],["TOM","That’s better but we’re not there yet.",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. liviNG ROOM - DAY - later",47,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom brings in a washing up bowl full of papier-mache which he lays at Barbara’s feet.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He lovingly applies the papier-mache to Barbara’s face. Filling in the holes. Building her a new cheek, new lips.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Enjoying himself.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As he works, he chats to Barbara.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["TOM","You know when I was in the office last week - or was it the week before? - I heard a really funny joke. It was about a policeman and a frog and damned if I can remember it. The punch line's something about a camel. Made me laugh like a drain.",48,"-","No"],["TOM","If only I could remember it. Tell you what: I'll look it up on the Internet - assuming the Internet's still a thing, which it was last time I checked.",48,"-","No"],["TOM","Now hold still or I'm likely to cut you and we don't want that, do we?",48,"-","No"],["TOM","Why am I so terrible at remembering jokes? Some people seem to have an endless supply of them but not me. I'm pretty much a joke free zone.",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When he is done, Barbara looks a lot like her old self\n    ",48,"-","No"],["TOM","You've got something on your chin.",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom takes out his handkerchief and spits on it. He dabs at Barbara’s chin until all the blood is gone.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["TOM","There now. That's better. As soon as your face has dried out, we’ll slap on some make-up and you’ll be looking as beautiful as ever.",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits down and puts the sound up on the television.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Dan Brody is on the Great British Shopping Experience.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","Well, I don't know about anyone else, but I for one am getting heartily fed up with all the government propaganda films messing up my broadcasting schedule.",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","OK - there's a zombie apocalypse. We get it! Now can we all just get on with our flipping lives, thank you very much?",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","And that’s all I need - my producer bleating in my ear. Apparently we can't say the word “zombie” because it's politically incorrect. Yes, Sandra, I know they're not zombies in the literal sense because they're not actually dead. So what do you want me to call them? Flesh-eating maniacs? Will flesh-eating maniacs do you? How about alternative carnivores?",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","Can I at least use the word apocalypse?",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","Because, Sandra, it is a fucking apocalypse, you dozy cow!",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","And now she's gone to the ladies to cry her eyes out - again! Oh boo \n      hoo\n       \n      hoo\n      . Very mature, Sandra. Very mature! No wonder the BBC turned you down!",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","OK so where was I before I was so rudely interrupted? Oh yes - silk underwear. Now who doesn't like silk underwear - especially when it's this flimsy?",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara’s head lolls to one side. Her ear drops onto Tom’s lap.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom picks up the ear.\n    ",48,"-","No"],["TOM","Now where did I put the super glue?",48,"-","No"],["BRODY","Between you and me, ladies and gentlemen, I’m wearing a pair of these lovely panties right now and I’ve never been happier.",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LivING ROOM - night",48,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara are watching “It’s A Wonderful Life” on television. It’s the part where Jimmy Stewart’s character, George Bailey, bursts into the entrance hall crying ‘Mary’ and finds himself confronted \n      by,a\n       newspaper reporter a sheriff and Carter the bank examiner.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As the soppiness builds, Tom wipes a tear from his eye.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A JET ROARS by overhead.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom puts a loving arm around Barbara.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The television screen suddenly goes blank.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh what the hell! It was almost finished!",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The television starts to BLEEP.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP... BLEEP... BLEEP...\n    ",49,"-","No"],["TOM","No! Not now! Too early! I’m not ready.",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP...! BLEEP...! BLEEP...!\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEP!\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The room fills with green light.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom convulses. Starts to scream.\n    ",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLACKOUT:",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - NIGHT - LATER",49,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Fade in:",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the television: \n    ",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","THE GREAT BRITISH SHOPPING EXPERIENCE IS OFF THE AIR\nWE'LL BE BACK SOON\n    ",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom wakes. He spends a few moments taking stock of himself.\n    ",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He looks at Barbara and can no longer deny the reality of her death.\n    ",50,"-","No"],["TOM","Sic transit \n      gloria\n       \n      mundi\n      .",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom kisses Barbara on the forehead.\n    ",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He fetches her make-up bag and touches up her face for her.\n    ",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - day",50,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is on the settee next to Barbara. Eating baked beans straight from the can.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the television: \n      NORMAL SERVICE WILL BE RESUMED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The screen goes blank.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["ANNOUNCER","There now follows an announcement from the Right Honourable Arthur Cavell, Prime Minister of the United Kingdom.",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom flicks a spoonful of baked beans at the screen.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["TOM","Wanker\n      .",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Television cuts to the Prime Minister’s office.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Cavell is sat behind a desk looking at camera.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["CAVELL","My fellow citizens, these are without doubt the darkest days our nation has ever faced. We are in the midst of an emergency so dire I was left with no choice but to declare martial law - to effectively turn these hallowed isles, this bastion of democracy, into a police state.",51,"-","No"],["CAVELL","It was not an easy decision to make, nor one I made lightly, and I am truly sorry for the pain it has caused so many of you.",51,"-","No"],["CAVELL","Unfortunately, since the imposition of martial law, things have gotten worse, not better. The horrendous effects of the so-called Black Knight satellite coupled with mass desertion within the armed forces has rendered martial law ineffective as a means of keeping order. Therefore, I hereby decree that it is at an end. You may leave the safety of your houses if you so wish.",51,"-","No"],["CAVELL","To put it bluntly, it is now every man for himself. Do whatever you must in order to survive.",51,"-","No"],["CAVELL","Good luck and may God preserve us all.",51,"-","No"],["TOM","Fuck off.",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The screen goes blank. Stays blank.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom flicks through channel after channel. All are blank.\n    ",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Tom’s office - day",51,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is at his PC. On \n      YouTube\n      , he does a search for ‘Black Knight’, which returns hundreds of thousands of videos to choose from.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He spots a video by Martin MCGREW.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["TOM","OK, Martin 'Daddy was a Martian' \n      McGrew\n      . Let's hear what you've got to say.",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom clicks on the video in question.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","McGrew\n       speaks to camera from his bedroom.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","In 1981, weirdo science-fiction author Philip K Dick published a novel that at the time seemed whacky and implausible but which in hind-sight was somewhat prescient.",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","The novel was called VALIS - VALIS being an acronym for Vast Active Living Intelligence System.",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","Imagine if you will a mysterious artificial satellite of extra-terrestrial origin that has been orbiting planet Earth for thousands of years. No, I'm not talking about the Black Knight. I'm talking about VALIS.",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","The parallels between VALIS and the Black Knight are more than a little unsettling but there was one difference which not only set them apart from one another it made them polar opposites. VALIS as Dick saw it was benevolent, a force for good, built with the explicit purpose of guiding mankind towards wisdom and understanding while keeping us free from tyranny.",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","There are those amongst us who believe that whether he knew it or not, Dick had hit upon a secret kept from the human race for millennia. I myself am certain that this is true.",52,"-","No"],["MCGREW","Stick with me and I will show you proof that VALIS is real and that it and the Black Knight were constructed by two alien races who fought a war on this planet millions of years ago…",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","OS: Detective Inspector WARBURG is KNOCKING on the front door.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is irritated. Ignores the KNOCKING.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","It continues.\n    ",52,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Mr. Caxton! Open up! This is the police. Open up or I will break down your door.",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","KNOCK! KNOCK! KNOCK!\n    ",52,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Mr. Caxton! You are not in any trouble but if you do not open this door I will have no choice but to arrest you!",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","KNOCK! KNOCK! KNOCK!\n    ",52,"-","No"],["TOM","All right! I'm bloody coming! Keep your fucking hair on!",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Harassed, Tom goes down to -\n    ",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. HALLWAY - DAY",52,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","KNOCK! KNOCK! KNOCK!\n    ",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The front door is full of bullet holes.\n    ",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Mr. Caxton! This is your last warning! Open up or else!",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","KNOCK! KNOCK! KNOCK!\n    ",53,"-","No"],["TOM","For \n      Chrissakes\n      ! Give it a rest!",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom drags the table away from the door. Unchains and opens the door.\n    ",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","About time.",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg flashes his warrant card, puts it straight back in his pocket.\n    ",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Mr. Caxton? Mr. Tom Caxton?",53,"-","No"],["TOM","Yes.",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Detective Inspector Warburg. Mind if I come in?",53,"-","No"],["TOM","The house is a mess.",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Right now, every house is a mess, Mr. Caxton. Every street. Every town, city and village.",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","If I spot your Y-fronts peeking out from under a chair, I promise not to faint.",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg takes Tom's silence as an invitation and steps over the threshold. \n    ",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","That the living room there, is it?",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg pushes open the living room door.\n    ",53,"-","No"],["WARBURG","A cup of tea would be nice.",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom follows Warburg into -\n    ",53,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LivING ROOM - DAY - coNTINUOUS",53,"-","No"],["TOM","No water. No gas. And pretty soon I expect we’ll have no electricity.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Oh well. Never mind.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg spots Barbara’s corpse on the settee but says nothing about it.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Take a seat, will you, Mr. Caxton?",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits next to Barbara.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg nods in the direction of Mr. Kepler.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","I see you have a corpse, Mr. Caxton. I must commend you on how well you’ve wrapped him.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","My neighbour.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Did you kill him?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I throttled him to death. Are you going to arrest me?",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","To what end, Mr. Caxton?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","It wasn’t the Black Knight. I deliberately and quite consciously killed him.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","I'm sure you had your reasons and I'm not here to judge you. I'm here to find out about the man who was shot on your doorstep: a Mr. Joseph Miller. Did you know him?'",54,"-","No"],["TOM","No.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Then can you explain why he came to your house when there was a curfew on?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","There were soldiers chasing after him. I think he just made a beeline for the nearest house.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Any port in a storm, hey? I suppose that makes sense.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg takes out his note pad and pencil. He wets the tip of the pencil with his tongue.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Tell me what happened.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I really didn't see anything. I was sitting at the table over there playing \n      Cluedo\n       with my wife.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","When you say your wife, I presume you mean the lady sitting next to you?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","Yes. Barbara, this is Detective Inspector Warburg. Detective Inspector Warburg - Barbara.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Delighted to meet you, Mrs. Caxton.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","She's the reason I killed Mr. Kepler. He ate half her face. I don't know if you can tell.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","It's not immediately obvious.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I used papier-mâché to fill in the missing bits.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Ingenious. You've done a very good job.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","Thank you.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Now, these soldiers - did they give any warnings before they shot Mr. Miller?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I heard one of them shout “Stop or we'll shoot”.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","“Stop or we’ll shoot.”",54,"-","No"],["TOM","He shouted it twice.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","And did Mr. Miller stop?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","No. He came running up to my front door.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Thereby disobeying a lawful order! I see. And I take it, judging from the state of the front door, that he was right on your doorstep when they shot him.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","He was pounding on the door, begging me to let him in.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Just as well you didn’t, Mr. Caxton. Otherwise the soldiers might have shot you too. And your lovely wife.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg puts away his notebook and pencil.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Well, you’ve told me all I need to know. Thank you for your cooperation, Mr. Caxton.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","When I get back to the station, I'll have the desk sergeant post you a compensation form. There's no reason for the army not to reimburse you for your door. They could have dragged Mr. Miller out into the street and shot him there. But that’s the military for you - no respect for property.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Incidentally, Mr. Caxton, you do know your wife is dead, don't you?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I’ve been meaning to wrap her up like the government says, but I haven’t gotten around to it.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Can’t quite bring yourself to say goodbye, I suppose. Perfectly understandable.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Do you mind if I take a closer look?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","Be my guest.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg kneels before Barbara and takes her hand in his. He flexes her finger.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","I’m impressed, Mr. Caxton. I truly am. You’re not a mortician by any chance?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","No. I’m a commercial artist.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Perhaps you should consider a career change. Morticians are in huge demand right now. There’s quite a backlog of stiffs building up.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg stands and leans forward. He looks like he is about to kiss Barbara. Instead, he sniffs her cheek.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Have you noticed that the dead smell different now?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I've not had the opportunity to sniff that many corpses.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Well, that's the thing about my job, Mr. Caxton. I've seen them dredged out of canals, hanging from trees, lying in the smouldering ashes of burnt-out buildings looking like massive chunks of charcoal, wedged in drains, laid out on mortuary slabs etc, etc.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","It’s funny, isn’t it? We all come into this world the same way, yet there are a million different ways to leave it.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","And every corpse is different to every other corpse except in one respect - the smell, Mr. Caxton. All corpses smell the same - except since the Black Knight the smell is different. It's richer. Spicier. More - and I hesitate to use this word, Mr. Caxton, but it's the only one that fits - sexier!",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","You wouldn’t think - would you? - that there could be anything sexy about a corpse, and yet...",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","It's that green light the Black Knight pumps out. Some people say it's \n      orgone\n       energy - the very essence of life - and I think they’re right.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","You've got to admit, Mr. Caxton, that since the Black Knight started doing the rounds, you've felt more alive than ever.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I suppose I have.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","And randier! It’s as if you're on steroids. Personally, I'm like a teenager again. I only have to see a woman and I'm rock hard. Especially dead ones.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","I think you’d best leave, Inspector.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","My wife died during the first transit. I woke up to find my hands around her throat and her tongue in the back of my throat. After I got over my initial shock, I realised I had a boner that could have taken someone’s eye out. And with my wife still warm... Well, you’re a man of the world, Mr. Caxton. I don’t have to tell you what happened next.",54,"-","No"],["TOM","Bloody hell, man! You’re sick.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","I keep my wife’s csdaver in the freezer. Treat me nice and I’ll thaw her out for you. Of course, I’d expect a bit of quid pro quo, if you know what I mean.",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Would you be interested in a foursome, Mr. Caxton?",54,"-","No"],["TOM","Get away from my wife!",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom jumps up. Drags Warburg away from Barbara.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg seems to find it funny.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Enraged, Tom kicks Warburg in the face. \n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg lands on his back. Tom dives on top of his.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The two men tussle.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","That’s it, Mr. Caxton. Release all that sexual tension. Beat me to a pulp then rape me!",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom rabbit punches Warburg in the kidneys. Punches him in the face.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg dislodges Tom. Manoeuvres him onto his back. Straddles Tom. Punches him.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In desperation, Tom grabs at Warburg’s crotch, aiming for his scrotum but grabbing his erect penis instead.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Now you’re talking.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom twists Warburg’s penis, throwing him off-balance. Sits up suddenly.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg lands up on his back again.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom wraps his hands around Warburg’s throat. \n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","That’s it. Squeeze harder now... Harder!",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom squeezes harder. It is not enough for him. So he leans down and bites Warburg’s ear. Comes up with the ear in his mouth.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He spits the ear in Warburg’s face.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg couldn’t be happier.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom continues to throttle Warburg.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["WARBURG","Sweet Jesus! I’m coming.",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Disgusted, Tom lets go of Warburg’s throat. Jumps to his feet.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The \n      realisation\n       that he’s just killed the policeman excites him. He turns to his wife, hands on hips, chest thrust out, basking in her (imaginary) adoration.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His hands strays to the front of his trousers.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He all but throws himself at Barbara. Kisses her ruined mouth. Runs a hand up her leg.\n    ",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. LIVING ROOM - DAY - LATER",54,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is sitting on the floor, his back against the wall. Crying. Looking apologetically at Barbara.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Miserable, defeated, Tom gets up and drags Detective Inspector Warburg’s lifeless body across the room and dumps it next to Mr. Kepler.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Then he slopes off out of the room, returning shortly with a bottle of whisky.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He sits down next to Barbara. Turns on the television.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On comes Dan Brody and the Great British Shopping Channel.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["TOM","Look, dear. Your favourite presenter.",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom starts on the whisky, drinking straight from the bottle.\n    ",55,"-","No"],["BRODY","Well, what can I say, ladies and gentlemen? If I didn't see it with my own two eyes, I just would not believe it! Less than twenty quid for a pair of cushions fit for a king.",55,"-","No"],["BRODY","I tell you, if His Majesty himself parked his \n      arse\n       on one of these he'd be ruined for other cushions for life. Let's get a close up - can we, Henry? - so our wonderful viewers can feast their eyes on the glory of this stitching. You see that? You wouldn’t find better stitching on a \n      Gucci\n       bag. And this silky finish - hmmm so smooth, so sexy. I tell you, folks, this cushion is so sensuous I’d happily fuck it! In fact, as soon as my shift is over, I’m off to the stock room to have me a cushion gang bang!",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - morning",55,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, empty whisky bottle at his feet, wakes up on the settee with a massive hangover.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","On the television: Dan Brody and the \n      GBSE\n       channel.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["BRODY","They're coming back! It's not over. It will never be over.",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom gropes around for the remote control and fails to find it.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He closes his eyes.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["BRODY","We thought it was as bad as it could get but we were wrong. The situation is worse than ever! Dear God, when will this nightmare end? It won’t will it? It will never end!",56,"-","No"],["BRODY","I didn’t believe in the devil because I didn’t believe in God. Now, I still don’t believe in God but I do believe in the devil! People, there is evil afoot. Trust no-one, not even the dead. Especially not the dead!",56,"-","No"],["BRODY","If you see a corpse, burn it! Do you hear me? BURN IT!",56,"-","No"],["BRODY","The dead are coming back. Oh God, they’re coming back!",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom’s hand closes around the remote. He turns off the television.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Relieved to be no longer having to listen to the ranting of Dan Brody, he opens his eyes.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Seconds later, he throws up.\n    ",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. BEDROOM - DAY",56,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom strips to his underwear. Washes himself as best he can with bottles of mineral water, heedless of the carpet.\n    ",57,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He finds clean clothes. Gets dressed.\n    ",57,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - day",57,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom opens a tin of stewing steak. Eats it directly from the can.\n    ",58,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. HallWAY - DAY",58,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom drags Warburg’s body up the stairs.\n    ",59,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Onto -\n    ",59,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Landing - day - continuous",59,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","- and then into -\n    ",60,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Tom’S OFFICE - day - continUOUS",60,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom dumps Warburg’s body on the floor. He rushes out. Returns shortly with a tee shirt, a leather jacket, Barbara’s make-up bag and a \n      chainsaw\n      . \n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Standing over Warburg, Tom starts the \n      chainsaw\n      . Gleefully waves it around. Brings it towards Warburg as if he is about to cut through him.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom kills the \n      chainsaw\n      . Kisses it.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He then removes Warburg’s upper clothing and replaces it with the tee shirt and jacket.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When Warburg is dressed again, Tom manoeuvres him onto the leather chair.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom seems very happy as he sets about transforming Warburg’s face into that of Butcher Baby.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","When he is done, he equips Warburg with the \n      chainsaw\n       then uses his phone to photograph “Butcher Baby”.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom transfers the photos to his PC and uses them to dummy up some promo posters.\n    ",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LiviNG ROOM - DAY",61,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom enters carrying a copy of “The Call of the Wild” by Jack London.\n    ",62,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He sits next to Barbara.\n    ",62,"-","No"],["TOM","My favourite book - “Call of the Wild” by Jack London. I keep threatening to read it to you and there’s no time like the present.",62,"-","No"],["TOM","Between you and me, I need something to do. Nobody warned me the end of the world would be this boring.",62,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom opens “Call of the Wild” and begins to read it out loud.\n    ",62,"-","No"],["TOM","Chapter 1. Into the primitive.",62,"-","No"],["TOM","Buck did not read the newspapers, or he would have known that trouble was brewing, not alone for himself, but for every tide-water dog, strong of muscle and with warm, long hair, from Puget Sound to San Diego. Because men, groping in the Arctic darkness, had found a yellow metal, and because steamship and transportation companies were booming the find, thousands of men were rushing into the Northland. These men wanted dogs, and the dogs they wanted were heavy dogs, with strong muscles by which to toil, and furry coats to protect them from the frost.",62,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - night",62,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Sat next to Barbara, Tom is watching BBC News which is showing a shot inside an Apollo module with a caption: \n      LIVE from inside the White Knight Mission Capsule.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Louise Bates again.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["BATES","Until this moment, Neil Armstrong was undoubtedly the world's most famous astronaut, but surely from here on in, the names of these two brave men - \n      Jurgen\n       Fischer and Walter Penrose - will eclipse even that of the first man on the moon.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","The picture you are seeing comes from a hand-held camera inside an Apollo command and service module which is more or less above the terminator - that is to say the division between night and day. On the night side, towards where the module is heading, you can see much of the Middle East bathed in green light, the significance of which can be lost on no-one.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","It makes one sick to think of the mayhem underway wherever the green light seeds its evil - the madness and the murder, the cold, calculated genocide perpetrated by an alien civilisation that for all any of us knows may no longer even exist.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Bates falls silent, her commentary giving way to radio chatter between Ground Control and the two astronauts, FISCHER and PENROSE.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["PENROSE","Houston, we're all set to go here. The White Knight is primed.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","\nBEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["GROUND CONTROL","Roger that, Walter.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["PENROSE","I have a visual sighting of the Black Knight. It's hard to make out because it really is black. About the only thing I can say about it is that it's quite irregular in shape and it looks... well, it looks evil.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["GROUND CONTROL","Roger that, Walter.",63,"-","No"],["GROUND CONTROL","Jurgen\n      , is there any chance you can get it on camera for us?",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["FISCHER","Roger, Houston.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","For a few seconds, as the camera is swung about, the picture goes mental, becoming a fleeting segue of nonsensical images before settling down into a view from the front of the capsule.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In the midst of the blackness of space can be seen something even blacker, only discernible because it is blocking out the stars behind it.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","This is the Black Knight satellite.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["BATES","And there we have it! The first close-up image of the Black Knight satellite! What a moment this is!",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The command module drifts ever closer to the satellite with each moment bringing with it slightly more detail. As the alien craft fills the screen, it is possible to make out what looks like portholes with sheets of black metal filling in for glass. All sorts of box-shaped artefacts protrude from its main shell, giving the impression of an agglomeration of spare parts rescued from a scrap yard and randomly thrown together.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["PENROSE","Houston, I can see many dents in the hull of that thing. I'm guessing they were made by meteors but who knows? Maybe the Black Knight once came under attack?",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["GROUND CONTROL","Roger that, Walter.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["PENROSE","We are applying \n      retros\n       to maintain our distance. This is as near as the command module goes. Requesting permission to commence the next phase of our mission, Houston.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BEEP.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["GROUND CONTROL","Permission is granted. Proceed at your own pace and God bless and God speed.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","\nSomething resembling a domestic fridge floats into view.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["BATES","And that, ladies and gentlemen, is what NASA is calling the White Knight, for obvious reasons. Without further details, we can only assume it to be an atomic weapon of some sort. The two astronauts are steering it towards the Black Knight.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","This is far closer than any earthly weapon has ever been to the deadly satellite. Come to that, no man has ever been as close to it as these two brave astronauts whose lives are very much on the line right now.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","The plan seems to be to somehow attach the White Knight to the Black Knight and detonate it at what amounts to point blank range guaranteeing total annihilation of this hideous artefact.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","Dear god, dare we believe that our salvation is unfolding right before our very eyes? Is this the end of the nightmare?",63,"-","No"],["BATES","We know not from whence the Black Knight came, nor who sent it or why. What we do know is -",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","White light suddenly bursts forth on the television screen and dies abruptly. The screen is now blank.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","A few moments of indecipherable background chatter gives way to the voice of Louise Bates.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["BATES","Ladies and gentlemen, it seems that the White Knight - whatever it is or rather was - has detonated prematurely. Thankfully, it went off within a hundred or so metres of its target which must surely mean the end of the Black Knight.",63,"-","No"],["BATES","Sadly, however, two brave astronauts - \n      Jurgen\n       Fischer and Walter Penrose - have sacrificed their lives to save humanity and in doing so have written their names large across the sky and joined the pantheon of immortal heroes.",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","\nTom laughs at Bates’ cornball phraseology.\n    ",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - night",63,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","From the cupboard under the sink, he digs out a box of ant poison. Reads the \n      bumf\n       on the box.\n    ",64,"-","No"],["TOM","Destroys ants without mercy. Guaranteed 100% effective. Warning: not for human consumption. Ingestion may cause death.",64,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom takes the box out to - \n    ",64,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Ext. Garden - night",64,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom stands contemplating the Milky Way for a while, perhaps seeking signs of the supposedly destroyed Black Knight.\n    ",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He then turns on the porch light and kneels down in front of the ants nest.\n    ",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Opens the box and prepares to pour its contents onto the nest.\n    ",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom finds he can’t do it. The ants have done him no harm. What right has he to rain destruction down upon them?\n    ",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Reconciled, he goes back indoors.\n    ",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Living room - later",65,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom, on the settee, swigs whisky. On the television - Louise Bates has radiates despair and defeat.\n    ",66,"-","No"],["BATES","Ladies and gentlemen, we have just received the worst news possible. The Black Knight has not been destroyed. Repeat: the Black Knight has not been destroyed. It is still functioning.",66,"-","No"],["BATES","The White Knight mission has failed. This is the end. Truly the fucking end of everything. All I can do now is advise you all to do what I intend to do - find a painless way out of this \n      shithouse\n       of a world as soon as possible.",66,"-","No"],["BATES","Goodbye and God bless.",66,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. Kitchen - nIGHT",66,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom takes a glass. Pours a large amount of ant poison into it.\n    ",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes to fill the glass with water. Of course, there is no water.\n    ",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He searches the food cupboard and comes upon a bottle of lemonade.\n    ",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He fills the glass with lemonade. Stirs the mixture.\n    ",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Goes to -\n    ",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. LiviNG ROOM - day - continuous",67,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom sits on the settee.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Battling against his gag reflex, he downs the ant poison and somehow manages to keep it down.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He lies on his side and waits for the end.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","His phone rings. He answers it.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Tom Caxton.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Congratulations! As a mobile phone owner you have been automatically entered into the National Smart Phone Lottery sponsored by Apple Computers in order to promote the use of smart phones. And guess what? You are this week's lucky winner of one million dollars. Yes, that's right: one million dollars. To claim your prize -",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom kills the call. Tosses aside the phone.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The phone rings again. He retrieves it from where he dropped it and answers.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Tom Caxton.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh, Mr. Caxton! Thank God! I hope you don't mind me calling like this, only I've been every number on my own phone and nobody's answering. I think everybody's dead - or at least everybody I know is. Except you and me, Mr. Caxton.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","We could be the last people on Earth, which I suppose is one for the history books, only now there won't be any more history books because there's no more history.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","The reason I'm calling you, Mr. Caxton is that I'm dying.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh my God! Now that I’ve said it, it’s suddenly become real. I am dying! This is it. My life is over.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Sixty sleeping pills. Little red things that look like sweets. Mother’s little helpers, I think they call them.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I took them one at a time and after each one, I said a Hail Mary.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I can feel them working - slowing down my heartbeat, slowing down my brain, shutting down my vital organs. It’s a nice feeling in a way but scary and I don’t want to die alone, Mr. Caxton, which is why I got on the phone like they tell you to do in the advert. You know the one I mean? Where you have all those lonely people phoning each other and suddenly they're not lonely any more and the sun comes out and the clouds just disappear?",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Are you a Catholic, Mr. Caxton? No, you're not. I remember that arsehole of a husband of mine saying you'd joined an atheist society, which - if you don't mind me saying so - is a very strange thing to do. Having a club for people who don't believe in God is like having a club for people who don't believe in the tooth fairy.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","The thing is, Mr. Caxton, I am a lifelong Catholic. Not a very devout one perhaps but I do confess my sins once in a while and here I am, committing the worst sin of all - suicide - and there's no priest around to grant me absolution.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","What little time I have left, I want to use squaring things with my god. I think I’m a good person, Mr. Caxton, and I think God thinks so too but I crave his forgiveness. I really do.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Do you mind hearing my confession, Mr. Caxton? I know you're not a priest but that doesn't matter. It won’t be you I’m talking to. It will be God.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I think you should know, Mrs. Lynton, I'm dying too. I've ingested ant poison.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Then as soon as I’ve confessed my sins, you should confess yours. Otherwise you're going to burn in Hell.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I don't believe in God and I don't believe in Hell.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Then I'm truly sorry because for you there is no salvation, no redemption.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Give me your confession, Mrs. Lynton.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","If I do, will you give me yours?",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Sure. Why not?",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I think I should begin with my worst sin. No - I've already told you that. Then let's start with my second worst sin, Mr. Caxton.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","What do they call it when someone kills their children? I know killing your brother is fratricide and killing your mum is matricide but what is it when it's your children? Never mind. It doesn't matter. Murder is murder.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I killed my children, Mr. Caxton.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I gave them a warm bath and fed them fish finger sandwiches washed down with Dr. Pepper laced with heroin. Did I tell you I'm a heroin addict, Mr. Caxton? That’s another sin to add to the list.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Beth and Peter went to sleep in each other's arms. They were happy because they were loved and they'd just had fish finger sandwiches. Then the Lord in his infinite mercy took their souls up to Paradise.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Oh, and one more sin while I think of it. I rejoiced at my husband losing his penis. I took pleasure in his pain.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Other than that, I have used the Lord's name in vain and I have committed the following sins: lust, greed, envy, pride and wrath. And I think that's about it.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","And now it's your turn, Mr. Caxton. Confess your sins before it’s too late.",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I don’t know how, Mrs. Lynton.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Imagine you’re standing before God. What do you want say to him?",68,"-","No"],["TOM","I want to say, “God, you blew it”.",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom convulses. Drops his phone. Clutches his stomach.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Cries out in agony.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Mr. Caxton? Are you OK?",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom is in his death throes. He screams and kicks and tears at his hair.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Jesus loves you, Tom Caxton. He knows you’re a good man.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","I’m praying, Mr. Caxton. I’m praying for both of us.",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom pays no attention to Isabelle. He is too busy dying to care.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Jesus loves me, this I know / for the Bible tells me so / Little ones to him belong; / they are weak but he is strong.",68,"-","No"],["ISABELLE","Yes, Jesus loves me! / Yes, Jesus loves me! / Yes, Jesus loves me! / The Bible tells me so.",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The pain intensifies.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Oh God, oh God! Make it stop! Make it stop!",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Isabelle sings on, growing ever quieter as her life slips away.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom crawls on the floor. Writhes. Sweats. Screams.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["TOM","Barbara!",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Eventually, he dies.\n    ",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","INT. HALLWAY - night - continuous",68,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Through the letter box comes an avalanche of packages. Each bears the logo of the Great British Shopping Experience.\n    ",69,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Int. living room - night - continuous",69,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The television switches to the Great British Shopping Experience Channel.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Dan Brody faces the camera with a \n      jerrycan\n       at his feet.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","This is the final testament of Daniel Reinhart Brody, star of stage and television.",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","By the time you view this - assuming there's anyone left to do so - I will be dead. More than dead: I will be ashes. My body will be gone for good. The Black Knight shall not have it!",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","People, heed my warning. Do not bury the dead. Destroy them utterly or they will come back.",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","They will come back!",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","Maybe, one day, there will be an end to this nightmare. Maybe they'll find a way to destroy the Black Knight. Maybe it will just switch itself off. Maybe some remnant of humanity will survive this catastrophe and start all over again.",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","Maybe. Maybe. Maybe.",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","But come the Day of Salvation, I for one will not be around to see it.",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Brody is the very picture of serenity as he picks up the \n      jerrycan\n       and douses himself in petrol.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","He takes out a lighter and thumbs the flint. As soon as he has a flame, he combusts with a loud \n      WHOOMF\n      !\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Screaming and flailing his arms, Brody runs at the camera causing it to white out. \n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Screen goes blank for a few seconds. Then we are back to the start of Brody’s last testament.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","This is the final testament of Daniel Reinhart Brody, star of stage and television.",70,"-","No"],["BRODY","By the time you view this - assuming there's anyone left to do so - I will be dead. More than dead: I will be ashes. My body will be gone for good.",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Screen goes blank. Sudden silence. Then...\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","BLEEP…! BLEEP…! BLEEP…!\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","The Black Knight approaches\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","As the BLEEPS merge one into the other, the room fills with green light.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","In the corner, the package containing old Mr. Kepler twitches. Re-animated, the old man struggles to free himself.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Detective Inspector Warburg opens his eyes. Rises.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom opens his eyes just as Barbara opens her one good one. They stand.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg, Tom and Barbara walk unsteadily towards each other.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Warburg lunges at Barbara. Tom and Barbara wrestle him to the ground.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara bites into Warburg’s neck, ripping out his windpipe.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom goes for the detective’s belly, tearing out chunks of flesh until his intestines are exposed. Tom pulls out the intestines. Starts eating them from one end.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Barbara starts on the other end.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","Tom and Barbara, united in half-death, lovingly munch their way towards one another.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FREEZE FRAME.\n    ",70,"-","No"],["NARRATOR","FINAL FADE OUT.",70,"-","No"]]}